var tafsirData_9 = {
  1: {
    "˹This is˺ a discharge from all obligations, by Allah and His Messenger,": "This is a formal announcement of complete disassociation and freedom from any treaty obligations. It comes directly from Allah and His Messenger Muhammad (peace be upon him), making it the highest level of divine decree. This declaration was made in the 9th year after Hijrah (migration to Medina), a time when the Muslim community had grown strong and many polytheists had repeatedly broken their peace agreements. The word 'discharge' means that the Muslims are no longer bound by treaties that the other party had already violated. This is similar to how in any agreement, if one party breaks the terms, the other party is released from their obligations. Ali ibn Abi Talib (may Allah be pleased with him) was sent to announce this declaration publicly during the pilgrimage season so everyone would hear it.",
    "to the polytheists you ˹believers˺ have entered into treaties with:": "This specifically addresses those idol-worshippers in Arabia with whom the Muslims had previously made peace treaties. Not all polytheists are meant here—only those who had shown treachery by breaking their agreements. The believers had made several treaties with various Arab tribes to establish peace, but many of these tribes violated the terms by secretly helping enemies against the Muslims or by attacking Muslim allies. This verse establishes an important principle: treaties are sacred, but when one party consistently breaks them, the other party has the right to annul the agreement."
  },
  2: {
    "\"You ˹polytheists˺ may travel freely through the land for four months,": "Even though the treaties were being annulled, Allah commanded that a grace period of four months be given. During this time, the polytheists could move freely, conduct their business, and travel safely throughout Arabia without fear of attack. This shows the justice and mercy in Islamic law—even when dealing with treaty-breakers, they were given fair warning and ample time to reconsider their position, make new arrangements, or accept Islam. This grace period began from the 10th of Dhul-Hijjah (the Day of Sacrifice) and extended for four complete months. This demonstrates that Islam does not believe in sudden, treacherous attacks but rather in clear communication and fair dealing.",
    "but know that you will have no escape from Allah,": "This is a serious warning that regardless of where they go or how they try to hide, no one can escape Allah's power and decree. They might feel safe during these four months, but they should use this time wisely because ultimately, everyone returns to Allah. This is a reminder that applies to all of humanity—no matter how powerful or clever someone thinks they are, they cannot outrun or outsmart the Creator of the universe. It encourages reflection and repentance rather than continued arrogance.",
    "and that Allah will disgrace the disbelievers.\"": "Those who persist in disbelief and opposition to the truth will face humiliation both in this world and the next. In this world, their plots will fail and their power will diminish. In the Hereafter, they will face an even greater disgrace. This is not a threat out of cruelty but a statement of reality—when people oppose the truth and break their promises repeatedly, the natural consequence is eventual failure and disgrace. History showed this to be true as Islam spread throughout Arabia within a short time."
  },
  3: {
    "A declaration from Allah and His Messenger ˹is made˺ to all people on the day of the greater pilgrimage": "This public announcement was made during the Hajj pilgrimage, specifically on the Day of Sacrifice (Yawm al-Nahr), which is the 10th of Dhul-Hijjah. This day is called 'the greater pilgrimage' because it is the peak of Hajj when the largest gathering of people occurs. The Prophet (peace be upon him) sent Ali ibn Abi Talib to make this announcement because it was customary among Arabs that treaties could only be annulled by the leader himself or a close family member. By choosing this time and place, the message would reach the maximum number of people since tribes from all over Arabia gathered for pilgrimage.",
    "that Allah and His Messenger are free of the polytheists.": "This declares that Allah and His Messenger have no responsibility or obligation toward those polytheists who broke their treaties. It is a complete severance of the relationship that had existed through peace agreements. This does not mean Muslims cannot have any dealings with non-Muslims in general—it specifically refers to those treaty-breakers who had proven themselves untrustworthy and hostile.",
    "So if you ˹pagans˺ repent, it will be better for you.": "Despite their betrayals, the door of repentance remains open. Allah, in His infinite mercy, still offers them the opportunity to turn back and accept the truth. If they abandon idol worship and embrace Islam, it will be the best thing for them—saving them from punishment in this world and the next, and granting them the honor of being part of the Muslim community. This shows that the ultimate goal is not fighting but guidance. As the Prophet (peace be upon him) said, \"For Allah to guide one person through you is better for you than the best type of camels\" (Bukhari and Muslim).",
    "But if you turn away, then know that you will have no escape from Allah.": "If they choose to reject this final offer of peace and guidance, they should understand that their fate is sealed. They cannot flee from Allah's power or hide from His knowledge. Every path they take, Allah is aware of it. This repetition from the previous verse emphasizes the seriousness of the situation.",
    "And give good news ˹O Prophet˺ to the disbelievers of a painful punishment.": "The word 'good news' here is used sarcastically to emphasize the certainty of what awaits them. Just as believers receive glad tidings of Paradise, disbelievers who persist in their rejection and hostility are 'informed' of their inevitable painful punishment. This rhetorical device makes the warning more impactful and memorable."
  },
  4: {
    "As for the polytheists who have honoured every term of their treaty with you": "This verse makes a crucial exception, demonstrating the justice of Islamic law. Not all polytheists are treated the same way. Those who kept their word, fulfilled all the conditions of their agreements, and remained faithful to their treaties are treated differently. Islam distinguishes between those who are honest and those who are treacherous, even among non-believers. The tribe of Banu Damrah and Banu Kinanah were examples of groups who honored their treaties completely.",
    "and have not supported an enemy against you,": "This adds another condition—they must not have secretly aided any enemy against the Muslims. Some tribes technically kept their direct agreements but helped others attack the Muslims behind the scenes. True faithfulness to a treaty means not working against your treaty partner in any way, directly or indirectly. This teaches an important principle about integrity in agreements.",
    "honour your treaty with them until the end of its term.": "Muslims are commanded to fulfill their agreements completely until the original end date, even if those agreements are with polytheists. This is a clear teaching that Muslims must be people of their word. Breaking a promise, even to an enemy, is forbidden. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said, \"The signs of a hypocrite are three: when he speaks he lies, when he makes a promise he breaks it, and when he is trusted he betrays\" (Bukhari and Muslim). This verse proves that Islam values honesty and integrity in all dealings.",
    "Surely Allah loves those who are mindful ˹of Him˺.": "Allah's love is connected to being mindful of Him (having taqwa), which includes keeping promises and dealing justly even with those who differ from us religiously. Taqwa is not just about prayer and fasting—it includes ethical behavior, honesty, and fairness in all transactions. This beautiful ending reminds believers that their integrity in worldly matters is an act of worship that earns Allah's love."
  },
  5: {
    "But once the Sacred Months have passed,": "After the four-month grace period ends, the situation changes. The polytheists have been given ample time to reflect, negotiate, leave, or accept Islam. The Sacred Months here refer to the four months of grace given to them, not the traditional four sacred months of the Islamic calendar. This waiting period shows that Islam is not hasty in matters of conflict and gives every opportunity for peaceful resolution.",
    "kill the polytheists ˹who violated their treaties˺ wherever you find them,": "This command specifically applies to those treaty-breakers who remained hostile after all peaceful options were exhausted. It is not a general command to kill all non-believers—context is crucial here. These were people who had broken their word, attacked Muslims and their allies, and refused all offers of peace. In the context of 7th-century Arabia, tribes in a state of war fought each other. The Muslims were simply being given permission to respond to aggression after being extremely patient. The bracketed phrase 'who violated their treaties' clarifies who is meant.",
    "capture them, besiege them, and lie in wait for them on every way.": "These are military tactics for dealing with an active enemy. Capturing enemies, surrounding their strongholds, and setting up strategic positions are standard practices in any conflict throughout history. This was a state of war against those who had repeatedly proven themselves enemies of the Muslim community. It's important to understand this is not about civilians but about combatants who posed a real threat.",
    "But if they repent, perform prayers, and pay alms-tax, then set them free.": "Even in the midst of military operations, the verse immediately opens the door for peace. If the enemy accepts Islam—demonstrated by repentance, establishing prayer, and paying zakah—all hostilities must cease immediately. They become brothers in faith with full rights. This shows the purpose is never bloodshed but rather guidance. The moment someone sincerely converts, their past is forgiven, and they are welcomed completely. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said, \"Islam erases what came before it\" (Muslim).",
    "Indeed, Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "This beautiful ending reminds us that Allah's primary attributes are forgiveness and mercy. Despite all the hostile actions these polytheists committed—breaking treaties, killing Muslims, persecuting believers—Allah is still willing to forgive them completely if they repent. This should give hope to every sinner that no matter how grave their past, Allah's mercy is greater."
  },
  6: {
    "And if anyone from the polytheists asks for your protection ˹O Prophet˺, grant it to them": "This verse reveals the remarkable compassion in Islamic teachings. Even during active conflict, if any individual polytheist comes seeking protection and safety, Muslims must grant it to them. No questions asked, no suspicion—simply provide them protection. This could be someone curious about Islam, someone caught in the middle of the conflict, or even a former enemy having second thoughts. The command is unconditional: grant them safety.",
    "so they may hear the Word of Allah,": "The purpose of granting protection is not political advantage but spiritual opportunity. Give them the chance to learn about Islam, hear the Quran, and understand the message without pressure or fear. This is dawah (invitation to Islam) in its purest form—creating a safe space for someone to learn and reflect. There is no compulsion in religion (as stated in Surah Al-Baqarah 2:256), so they must be free to listen, think, and decide without coercion.",
    "then escort them to a place of safety,": "Even if they listen to the message and choose not to accept Islam, Muslims are still obligated to escort them safely back to their own territory. They came seeking protection, and that protection extends until they are completely safe—even if they reject the faith. This is extraordinary: in the middle of a conflict, you protect your enemy, teach them your beliefs, and then safely return them home regardless of their decision. This demonstrates that the goal is never to harm but to guide.",
    "for they are a people who have no knowledge.": "The reason given for this merciful treatment is that many polytheists opposed Islam out of ignorance, not malice. They simply did not understand the truth. Once they hear the Quran and learn about Islam properly, many would recognize its truth. This verse teaches Muslims to view opponents with compassion—perhaps they are misguided rather than evil, ignorant rather than wicked. This perspective softens hearts and promotes patient dawah."
  },
  7: {
    "How can such polytheists have a treaty with Allah and His Messenger,": "This rhetorical question expresses astonishment at the idea of trusting those who have repeatedly proven untrustworthy. After their history of breaking agreements, plotting against Muslims, and supporting enemies, how could any new treaty with them be meaningful? It's like asking, 'How can you trust someone who has lied to you ten times to tell the truth the eleventh time?' The question is meant to make the believers understand why the previous verses annulled the treaties.",
    "except those you have made a treaty with at the Sacred Mosque?": "Once again, an exception is made for those who made treaties at the Sacred Mosque (Masjid al-Haram) in Mecca and remained faithful. Some scholars say this refers to the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah or to specific tribes like Banu Kinanah who kept their word. The location—the Sacred Mosque—adds weight to the agreement, and those who honored such a sacred covenant deserve to have it honored in return.",
    "So, as long as they are true to you, be true to them.": "This is a beautiful principle of reciprocity and fairness. The relationship is conditional: as long as they keep their end of the bargain, Muslims must keep theirs. There's no preemptive breaking of treaties in Islam. Even suspicion is not enough reason to violate an agreement. Only actual breach by the other party justifies response. This principle builds trust and shows the world that Muslims are people of integrity.",
    "Indeed Allah loves those who are mindful ˹of Him˺.": "Again, keeping promises and dealing justly is connected to taqwa (mindfulness of Allah). A person who fears Allah and is conscious of being accountable to Him will naturally be honest in their dealings. This repetition emphasizes how important integrity is in Islam—it's not just good manners but an act of worship that earns Allah's love."
  },
  8: {
    "How ˹can they have a treaty˺? If they were to have the upper hand over you, they would have no respect for kinship or treaty.": "This verse exposes the true character of these particular polytheists. Their agreements were only tactical—kept when they were weak, broken when they felt strong. If they ever gained power over the Muslims, they would show no mercy, respecting neither family ties nor formal agreements. History had proven this: when the Quraysh and their allies had the upper hand, they persecuted Muslims brutally, killed them, and drove them from their homes. This verse reminds believers not to be naive about those who have already shown their true colors.",
    "They only flatter you with their tongues, but their hearts are in denial,": "Their words of peace and friendship are merely lip service. They say what you want to hear to buy time or gain advantage, but their hearts contain the opposite—hatred, rejection, and plans for betrayal. This is a warning about a specific type of enemy: those who use diplomacy as a weapon. The Prophet (peace be upon him) dealt with such people throughout his mission, and Allah is exposing their reality so believers won't be deceived.",
    "and most of them are rebellious.": "The majority of these treaty-breaking polytheists were fasiqun—people who transgress limits, break rules, and have no moral restraint. They rebelled against their own agreements, against basic ethics, and against the truth. This explains why treaties with them kept failing—their fundamental character was one of rebellion and dishonesty. Note that Allah says 'most,' not 'all,' showing precision and fairness even in criticism."
  },
  9: {
    "They chose a fleeting gain over Allah's revelations,": "These polytheists traded eternal truth for temporary worldly benefit. They rejected Allah's signs and the Prophet's message because accepting Islam would cost them their status, their idols' income, or their tribal pride. It's like someone who sells a diamond for a piece of candy—an incredibly foolish trade. The 'fleeting gain' could be money from pilgrims visiting their idols, political power, or simply the comfort of not changing their ways. Whatever it was, it was nothing compared to what they gave up.",
    "hindering ˹others˺ from His Way.": "Not content with their own rejection, they actively blocked others from accepting Islam. They spread lies about the Prophet (peace be upon him), threatened those who showed interest in Islam, and used their influence to turn people away from guidance. This is a greater sin than personal disbelief because they became obstacles to others' salvation. The Prophet (peace be upon him) and early Muslims faced tremendous opposition from these efforts.",
    "Evil indeed is what they have done!": "Allah Himself declares their actions to be evil. Rejecting truth is bad enough, but selling it for worldly gain and then preventing others from finding it—this is truly despicable behavior. This divine verdict should make anyone engaged in similar behavior reconsider immediately."
  },
  10: {
    "They do not honour the bonds of kinship or treaties with the believers.": "When dealing with Muslims, these polytheists abandoned all principles. Family relationships meant nothing—they would fight against their own Muslim relatives. Treaties meant nothing—they would break their word without hesitation. The persecution of early Muslims in Mecca demonstrated this: fathers tortured sons, tribes expelled their own members, and business agreements were violated—all because those Muslims had accepted Islam. The bonds that typically hold society together were discarded when it came to believers.",
    "It is they who are the transgressors.": "Allah definitively labels them as the aggressors, the ones who crossed boundaries. This is important because sometimes the polytheists portrayed themselves as victims or defenders of tradition. But Allah clarifies: they are the transgressors. They broke treaties, they attacked first, they violated norms of kinship and honor. Any military response from Muslims was not aggression but self-defense and justice."
  },
  11: {
    "But if they repent, perform prayer, and pay alms-tax,": "Despite all their crimes—breaking treaties, blocking people from Islam, transgressing against believers—the door of repentance remains wide open. If they sincerely turn back to Allah, establish regular prayer (showing their connection to Allah), and pay zakah (showing their connection to the Muslim community and care for the poor), everything changes. These three elements—repentance, prayer, and zakah—represent the complete transformation of a person from disbelief to faith.",
    "then they are your brothers in faith.": "This is revolutionary: yesterday's bitter enemy becomes today's beloved brother. There is no second-class citizenship in Islam, no lingering punishment for past sins after genuine repentance. The very people who tortured and killed Muslims, once they repent, become full brothers with equal rights and complete acceptance. Bilal (may Allah be pleased with him), who was brutally tortured by his master Umayyah ibn Khalaf, would later stand equal to any Qurayshi nobleman in the Muslim community. This is the beauty of Islamic brotherhood.",
    "This is how We make the revelations clear for people of knowledge.": "Allah explains His verses in detail for those who want to understand. The conditions are clear, the principles are established, and the path forward is explained. Those who truly seek knowledge will understand the wisdom behind these rulings—the justice, the mercy, and the perfect balance between firmness and compassion."
  },
  12: {
    "But if they break their oaths after making a pledge": "If after making new agreements, they once again break their promises—just as they did before—then their pattern of treachery is confirmed. One betrayal might be forgiven, but repeated violations after solemn pledges show a fundamental dishonesty that cannot be ignored. This applies to those who make peace and then violate it again.",
    "and attack your faith,": "Beyond political betrayal, if they mock, insult, and attack Islam itself, trying to undermine the believers' religion through propaganda and ridicule, this adds another dimension to their hostility. They're not just political enemies but ideological attackers trying to destroy the faith from within by spreading doubts and mockery. This combination of treaty-breaking and religious attack represents the most serious form of hostility.",
    "then fight the champions of disbelief—who never honour their oaths—": "The command is to fight the leaders, the 'champions of disbelief'—those who organize and lead the opposition, not random individuals. By targeting leadership, the source of the problem is addressed. These leaders are characterized as people whose oaths mean nothing; they have no concept of keeping their word. Throughout history, removing hostile leadership while sparing common people has been recognized as more effective and more humane.",
    "so perhaps they will desist.": "Even here, the goal is not annihilation but stopping their aggression. 'Perhaps they will desist'—meaning, hopefully the confrontation will make them stop their attacks, reconsider their ways, and cease hostilities. The objective of fighting in Islam is never revenge or conquest for its own sake but establishing peace and stopping oppression. If fighting achieves that goal, it has served its purpose."
  },
  13: {
    "Will you not fight those who have broken their oaths,": "Allah challenges the believers with a rhetorical question: with all this evidence of treachery, why would you hesitate to confront them? They have broken their oaths repeatedly, proving themselves untrustworthy. The question is designed to motivate action by highlighting the justice of the cause. It's not aggression; it's response to clear violations.",
    "conspired to expel the Messenger ˹from Mecca˺,": "These enemies had plotted to exile and even assassinate the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). The conspiracy to expel him from Mecca is well documented—the Quraysh leaders met in Dar al-Nadwa and planned to either imprison him, exile him, or kill him. They chose assassination, sending young men from multiple tribes so the blame would be distributed. Allah saved His Messenger, but the conspiracy was real and serious. How can such people be trusted?",
    "and attacked you first?": "This is crucial context often missed by critics of these verses. The Muslims did not start the conflict. The polytheists initiated hostilities through persecution, torture, economic boycott, and eventually military attacks. At Badr, Uhud, and other battles, the polytheists were the aggressors. This verse confirms that any fighting is defensive response, not offensive aggression. The Prophet (peace be upon him) and his companions endured years of persecution before ever fighting back.",
    "Do you fear them?": "Are you afraid of these treaty-breakers and aggressors? Fear is natural in humans, but Allah is asking believers to examine what they truly fear. The enemies seem powerful, their numbers large, their resources greater—but should this cause hesitation?",
    "Allah is more deserving of your fear, if you are ˹true˺ believers.": "This powerful statement reorients priorities. If you're going to fear anyone, fear Allah. He is more powerful than any enemy, more capable of harm or benefit. Fearing Allah means obeying His commands even when difficult, trusting His promise even when circumstances seem challenging. A true believer's primary concern is pleasing Allah, not avoiding conflict with His enemies. This principle applies beyond warfare—in all situations, fear of Allah should override fear of people's opinions, financial loss, or social pressure."
  },
  14: {
    "˹So˺ fight them and Allah will punish them at your hands,": "When believers fight in Allah's cause against legitimate enemies, they become instruments of divine justice. The punishment these aggressors receive in battle is actually Allah's punishment delivered through human hands. This elevates the act from mere fighting to carrying out divine decree. It also means that victory doesn't depend solely on human strength but on Allah's will and support.",
    "put them to shame,": "Beyond physical defeat, Allah promises to humiliate these arrogant enemies. They who mocked the believers, boasted of their power, and thought they were invincible would face public disgrace. For the proud Arabs of that time, shame was often worse than death. They would lose face before the entire Arabian Peninsula.",
    "help you overcome them,": "Allah promises victory and support. The small, poorly-equipped Muslim community would triumph over larger, better-resourced enemies. This promise was fulfilled repeatedly in early Islamic history. At Badr, 313 Muslims defeated over 1,000 Qurayshi fighters. Such victories could only be explained through divine assistance.",
    "and soothe the hearts of the believers—": "Many Muslims had suffered terribly at the hands of these polytheists. They had lost family members to torture, lost their homes and wealth to confiscation, and endured years of humiliation. Victory would bring healing to these wounded hearts. It would validate their patience, reward their sacrifice, and demonstrate that truth ultimately prevails. There's recognition here of the emotional and psychological needs of believers, not just the political necessities."
  },
  15: {
    "removing rage from their hearts.": "The believers had legitimate anger—righteous indignation at injustice, persecution, and oppression they had endured. Victory would release this pent-up emotion in a healthy way. Rather than festering into bitterness or unhealthy desire for revenge, the completion of justice would bring closure and peace. Allah cares about the emotional wellbeing of His servants, not just their physical safety.",
    "And Allah pardons whoever He wills.": "Even in this context of battle and victory, Allah reminds us of His mercy and power to forgive. Some of those enemies might repent—even on the battlefield, even at the last moment—and Allah can forgive them. No one is beyond redemption until their last breath. This keeps believers from developing hatred and reminds them that today's enemy might be tomorrow's brother. Many fierce opponents of Islam, like Khalid ibn al-Walid (may Allah be pleased with him), later became its greatest champions.",
    "For Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "Allah knows who deserves punishment and who deserves forgiveness. He knows what's in every heart. His decisions are based on perfect knowledge and perfect wisdom. Humans see external actions; Allah sees intentions, circumstances, and futures. So while believers carry out their duty to confront aggressors, they leave ultimate judgment to Allah, who knows and decides with wisdom beyond human comprehension."
  },
  16: {
    "Do you ˹believers˺ think that you will be left without Allah proving who among you ˹truly˺ struggles ˹in His cause˺": "Allah asks believers a profound question: did you think faith would be easy? Did you think you could claim to believe without being tested? Faith must be proven through action, especially through struggle (jihad) for Allah's cause. This includes physical struggle when necessary but also the daily struggle against one's desires, the struggle to be honest, the struggle to pray when tired, the struggle to give charity when money is tight. Allah wants to distinguish those whose faith is genuine from those whose faith is merely words.",
    "and never takes trusted allies other than Allah, His Messenger, or the believers?": "True believers don't secretly align themselves with enemies of Islam. They don't have hidden loyalties that contradict their public Muslim identity. Some hypocrites would publicly be Muslim but privately maintain close alliances with polytheists, sharing secrets or supporting them against believers. This verse emphasizes that a believer's primary loyalty must be to Allah, His Messenger, and the community of believers. This doesn't mean Muslims can't have normal dealings with non-Muslims, but their deepest trust and alliance must be with the Muslim community.",
    "And Allah is All-Aware of what you do.": "Nothing is hidden from Allah—not actions, not intentions, not secret conversations, not private thoughts. This is both a warning and a comfort. A warning to hypocrites that their duplicity will be exposed. A comfort to sincere believers that their genuine efforts, even those unseen by others, are known and valued by Allah. Every sacrifice made for His sake is recorded."
  },
  17: {
    "It is not for the polytheists to maintain the mosques of Allah": "The polytheists of Mecca took pride in being custodians of the Kaaba and hosts of pilgrims. They saw this as a great honor and virtue. But Allah declares that people who worship idols alongside Him have no right to maintain His houses of worship. It's a contradiction—how can you take care of a place dedicated to the One God while worshipping many gods? Their presence as caretakers was inappropriate and would now end as Islam spread throughout Arabia.",
    "while they openly profess disbelief.": "They don't even hide their disbelief—they openly practice idol worship, publicly reject Allah's Messenger, and make no secret of their polytheism. With such open contradiction, their role as mosque maintainers is illegitimate. This teaches that those who care for mosques should be people of faith who understand and respect what the mosque represents.",
    "Their deeds are void,": "Whatever 'good' they thought they were doing by maintaining the mosque is worthless in Allah's sight. Good deeds must be built on the foundation of faith and correct belief. Without that foundation, the deeds have no value, like building a beautiful house on sand—it will collapse. Feeding pilgrims, providing water, cleaning the Kaaba—none of these earn reward without belief in One God.",
    "and they will be in the Fire forever.": "The ultimate consequence of persistent disbelief is eternal punishment in Hell. This is stated clearly and seriously. The fact that they maintained a holy site will not save them. This should motivate anyone in a similar position to examine their beliefs, not just their actions."
  },
  18: {
    "The mosques of Allah should only be maintained by those who believe in Allah and the Last Day,": "Here are the qualifications for those who should care for mosques: first, belief in Allah (the One God, with His names and attributes) and belief in the Day of Judgment (accountability for all actions). These fundamental beliefs ensure the person understands the purpose of the mosque and respects its sanctity. Without these beliefs, maintaining a mosque is just a job, not an act of worship.",
    "establish prayer, pay alms-tax,": "The person should be active in worship—not just believing in theory but practicing. Establishing prayer means praying regularly and properly. Paying zakah shows they are part of the Muslim community's economic system of caring for the poor. These practical acts demonstrate living faith, not just intellectual acceptance.",
    "and fear none but Allah.": "They should not fear people's criticism, loss of income, social pressure, or any worldly consequence when it comes to matters of religion. Their primary fear is of Allah—fear of displeasing Him, fear of accountability to Him. This quality ensures they will maintain the mosque according to Allah's guidance, not according to politics or popular opinion.",
    "It is right to hope that they will be among the ˹truly˺ guided.": "People with these qualities have good reason to hope for guidance and success. The word 'hope' is used rather than certainty because ultimate judgment belongs to Allah, and no one should be arrogant about their own righteousness. But these qualities are strong indicators of genuine guidance. If you maintain mosques with these attributes, you're on the right path."
  },
  19: {
    "Do you ˹pagans˺ consider providing the pilgrims with water and maintaining the Sacred Mosque": "The Quraysh boasted about their roles as hosts of pilgrims—providing them with water (an honorable task in the desert) and taking care of the Kaaba. They thought these services made them superior and virtuous. Some even argued that their status should exempt them from accepting Islam or that it equaled the faith of the Muslims.",
    "as equal to believing in Allah and the Last Day and struggling in the cause of Allah?": "Allah directly compares their pride—giving water and maintaining a building—to true faith and its demands: believing in Allah, believing in the Last Day, and striving in His cause through hardship and sacrifice. Is filling water containers equal to facing persecution, leaving your home, and risking your life for truth? The comparison is almost absurd when stated clearly.",
    "They are not equal in Allah's sight.": "The verdict is clear and divine. These two things are not equivalent. External services, however impressive they look to people, cannot compare to internal faith and its resulting sacrifices. A person who believes and struggles for Allah is infinitely more valuable than one who provides physical services while rejecting the very God in whose name those services are offered.",
    "And Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people.": "Those who persist in this type of self-delusion—thinking their outward actions can substitute for true faith—are wrongdoers, and Allah will not guide them. They have chosen the wrong path and stubbornly remain on it. Guidance requires humility and willingness to change, which they lack."
  },
  20: {
    "Those who have believed, emigrated,": "The first two qualifications: faith in Allah and His Messenger, followed by emigration (hijrah). The early Muslims left their homes, families, and possessions in Mecca to escape persecution and establish a community where they could practice their religion freely in Medina. This emigration required immense sacrifice—leaving everything familiar for uncertainty. It proved the sincerity of their faith.",
    "and strived in the cause of Allah with their wealth and their lives": "Beyond believing and emigrating, they actively worked for Islam. They spent their money to support the cause—buying equipment, feeding soldiers, helping the poor. They risked their lives in defense of the Muslim community. This is jihad in its comprehensive sense: using everything you have—money, time, abilities, and even life itself—to serve Allah's cause.",
    "are greater in rank in the sight of Allah.": "These believers hold higher positions with Allah than anyone who merely performs outward services without faith. Ranks in the Hereafter are not determined by wealth or status on earth but by the sincerity and sacrifice of one's faith. A poor emigrant who struggled for Islam outranks any rich person who simply provided water to pilgrims without believing.",
    "It is they who will triumph.": "They are the true winners—in this world and the next. Their sacrifices will be rewarded. Their efforts will bear fruit. True success is not measured by worldly gain but by earning Allah's pleasure and Paradise. The early Muslims who sacrificed everything are the ultimate winners, regardless of how they appeared to worldly observers at the time."
  },
  21: {
    "Their Lord gives them good news of His mercy,": "Allah Himself delivers good news to these believers. The first blessing mentioned is mercy—Allah's compassion, forgiveness, and gentle treatment. They will be enveloped in divine mercy, their sins forgiven, their mistakes overlooked, their weaknesses covered. What greater gift could there be than the mercy of the Creator?",
    "pleasure,": "Even greater than mercy is Allah's pleasure (ridwan). He is pleased with them. Imagine the Creator of the universe being pleased with you! The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Allah will say to the people of Paradise, 'I will give you something better than all this,' and they will ask what could be better than Paradise. Allah will say, 'My pleasure. I will never be angry with you after this' (Bukhari and Muslim). This is the ultimate success.",
    "and Gardens with everlasting bliss,": "Paradise itself—gardens of unimaginable beauty, rivers, palaces, eternal happiness. And not temporary bliss but everlasting bliss. No fear of it ending, no aging, no death, no sadness. The bliss of Paradise is permanent, which is what makes it truly Paradise. Every pleasure on earth is shadowed by the knowledge it will end; in Paradise, that shadow doesn't exist."
  },
  22: {
    "to stay there for ever and ever.": "Emphasis on the eternal nature of Paradise. Forever. Without end. The human mind cannot fully grasp eternity, but this repetition helps us understand: there is no expiration date on Paradise. The struggles of this short life lead to infinite reward.",
    "Surely with Allah is a great reward.": "Whatever sacrifices believers make—leaving family for Allah, spending wealth for His cause, risking life in His path—the reward with Allah is far greater. No one who sacrifices for Allah ever loses out. The exchange rate is infinitely in the believer's favor. This verse concludes the section by emphasizing that everything good comes from Allah, and He has immense rewards stored for those who believe and strive."
  },
  23: {
    "O believers! Do not take your parents and siblings as trusted allies": "Allah addresses the believers directly with an important command about family relationships. Under normal circumstances, parents and siblings are among our closest relationships, deserving of love and good treatment. But this verse addresses a specific situation with important conditions explained next.",
    "if they choose disbelief over belief.": "The condition is crucial: this applies only if your family members actively choose disbelief over faith. They've been presented with the truth and rejected it, preferring their old ways. In such cases, while you must still treat them kindly and maintain family ties, you cannot make them your primary advisors, confidants, or allies in matters that affect your faith and the Muslim community. You cannot prioritize loyalty to them over loyalty to Allah. This was relevant to many early Muslims whose families opposed their faith violently.",
    "And whoever of you does so, they are the ˹true˺ wrongdoers.": "If someone takes disbelieving family members as their primary allies—following their guidance against Islamic principles, supporting them against believers, or prioritizing their approval over Allah's—then that person has wronged themselves. They've put creation before Creator, temporary relationships before eternal ones. This doesn't mean cutting off family entirely (which is forbidden) but about where ultimate loyalty lies when there's conflict."
  },
  24: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"If your parents and children and siblings and spouses and extended family": "The Prophet is commanded to deliver this challenging message. Allah lists the closest family relationships: parents who raised you, children you would die for, siblings who shared your childhood, spouses who share your life, and extended family (clan, tribe) who form your support network. These are the people humans naturally love most deeply.",
    "and the wealth you have acquired": "Beyond family, there's wealth—money, property, investments that you've worked hard to accumulate. People sacrifice so much of their lives to build financial security.",
    "and the trade you fear will decline": "Business concerns and career worries. The fear that following Islam strictly might hurt your business, cost you clients, or damage your career prospects. This is a real concern many Muslims face when their professional life seems to conflict with religious obligations.",
    "and the homes you cherish": "Your house, your comfort zone, your place of security and memories. The place you've decorated to your taste, the neighborhood you love, the community you're part of. These attachments are natural and not inherently wrong.",
    "—˹if all these˺ are more beloved to you than Allah and His Messenger and struggling in His Way,": "Here is the critical question: if any of these things—however good they are—become more beloved to you than Allah, more important than the Prophet's guidance, more precious than striving for Islam, then there's a problem. It's a question of priority. You can love your family and wealth, but not more than Allah. You can enjoy your home and business, but not at the cost of your faith. When there's a conflict between what Allah wants and what these things demand, which wins?",
    "then wait until Allah brings about His Will.": "This is a severe warning. If worldly attachments take priority over faith, then wait for the consequences. Wait for Allah's decree to unfold—which could be punishment in this world, or consequences in the Hereafter, or both. The tone is ominous because the matter is serious. Prioritizing creation over Creator is a form of subtle shirk (associating partners with Allah) in one's heart.",
    "Allah does not guide the rebellious people.\"": "Those who make this wrong choice are rebellious (fasiqun)—they've stepped outside the bounds of proper faith. And Allah withdraws His guidance from such people. Guidance is a gift that can be lost when one persistently makes wrong choices. This should frighten us into examining our priorities regularly: what do I truly love most? Would I give up my comfort for Allah's sake?"
  },
  25: {
    "Indeed Allah has given you ˹believers˺ victory on many battlefields,": "Allah reminds the believers of His continuous support throughout their struggles. They had experienced divine assistance at Badr against overwhelming odds, at the Trench when enemy armies surrounded Medina, and in many other situations. These victories were not due to superior numbers or weapons but due to Allah's help. This reminder sets up an important lesson about the source of true success.",
    "even at the Battle of Ḥunain when you took pride in your great numbers, but they proved of no advantage to you.": "The Battle of Hunain took place in the 8th year after Hijrah, shortly after the conquest of Mecca. The Muslim army numbered around 12,000—the largest force they had ever assembled. Some soldiers began feeling overconfident, with some reportedly saying, 'We cannot be defeated today due to our numbers.' This self-reliance was a subtle shift from trusting Allah to trusting themselves. The verse teaches that the moment you start relying on worldly means instead of Allah, those very means can fail you. Numbers, weapons, technology—none of these guarantee success without Allah's permission.",
    "The earth, despite its vastness, seemed to close in on you,": "When the enemy tribe of Hawazin ambushed them in the valley, the large Muslim army fell into chaos. The open valley suddenly felt suffocating as arrows rained down from hidden positions. This vivid description captures the psychological terror of the moment—when panic strikes, even vast spaces feel like prisons. The same army that felt invincible moments before now felt trapped and helpless.",
    "then you turned back in retreat.": "The mighty army of 12,000 actually fled. This was a humiliating moment that Allah allowed to happen to teach a crucial lesson: victory comes only from Him. The same believers who had triumphed at Badr with 313 men were now retreating with 12,000. The difference was not in numbers but in where they placed their trust. This incident humbled them and corrected their perspective."
  },
  26: {
    "Then Allah sent down His reassurance upon His Messenger and the believers,": "After the initial chaos, Allah intervened. He sent down 'sakinah'—a special divine tranquility and calm that settles in the heart. The Prophet (peace be upon him) stood firm during the retreat, calling out to the fleeing soldiers. This supernatural calm spread from him to the believers, stopping their panic and restoring their courage. The Prophet called out, 'I am the Prophet, this is no lie! I am the son of Abdul-Muttalib!' His uncle Abbas, who had a powerful voice, called the companions to return, and they rallied back.",
    "and sent down forces you could not see,": "Allah sent angels to assist the believers. These invisible reinforcements are a reminder that the battlefield has dimensions beyond human perception. While humans see only physical armies, Allah commands forces unseen. This happened at Badr as well, where thousands of angels fought alongside the Muslims. The unseen help emphasizes that ultimate power belongs to Allah, not to any earthly force.",
    "and punished those who disbelieved. Such was the reward of the disbelievers.": "The battle eventually turned, and the Hawazin and Thaqif tribes were defeated. Their punishment in this world was military defeat, but it also serves as a glimpse of what awaits persistent disbelievers in the Hereafter. The phrase 'reward of the disbelievers' is used ironically—their 'reward' for opposing truth was punishment and humiliation."
  },
  27: {
    "Then afterwards Allah will turn in grace to whoever He wills.": "Even after the defeat, the door of repentance remained open for the enemy. Many from Hawazin and Thaqif eventually embraced Islam. The chief of Thaqif, who had fought fiercely against the Muslims, later became Muslim. This shows that today's enemy might be tomorrow's brother. Allah's plan is not revenge but guidance. The battle was a means to break their arrogance so they could receive the truth. And indeed, many did.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "This beautiful ending reminds us that Allah's primary attributes are forgiveness and mercy. He defeats enemies not out of cruelty but to open paths for their eventual guidance. Anyone who sincerely repents—even after fighting against Islam—can be forgiven. This should give hope to every sinner and prevent believers from ever despairing of Allah's mercy or writing off any person as beyond redemption."
  },
  28: {
    "O believers! Indeed, the polytheists are ˹spiritually˺ impure,": "Allah addresses the believers with an important ruling. The impurity mentioned here is spiritual, not physical. It refers to the impurity of their beliefs—associating partners with Allah, worshipping idols, and rejecting the truth. Some scholars note that a polytheist's body is not physically impure (najis), as the Prophet (peace be upon him) interacted with them normally. The impurity is in their creed and the spiritual corruption that comes with idol worship. The bracketed word 'spiritually' clarifies this meaning.",
    "so they should not approach the Sacred Mosque after this year.": "From the 9th year after Hijrah onwards, polytheists were prohibited from entering the Sacred Mosque and the Haram area of Mecca. This was announced during the Hajj when Ali ibn Abi Talib (may Allah be pleased with him) proclaimed the verses of Surah At-Tawbah. The sacred precincts dedicated to the worship of the One God should not be visited by those who worship others besides Him. This ruling restored the Kaaba to its original purpose as a house built by Ibrahim (peace be upon him) for monotheistic worship.",
    "If you fear poverty, Allah will enrich you out of His bounty, if He wills.": "This addresses a practical concern. The Meccans had significant economic gains from polytheist pilgrims—trade, hospitality, services. If polytheists were banned, would the economy collapse? Allah reassures them not to let financial fears prevent them from implementing His command. When you obey Allah, He provides from unexpected sources. After this ruling, Islam spread rapidly throughout Arabia, and the number of Muslim pilgrims far exceeded what the polytheists had brought. Allah's promise proved true.",
    "Surely, Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "Allah knows the believers' concerns and the economic implications. His command is based on perfect wisdom that considers factors humans may not understand. When we obey divine commands even when they seem economically disadvantageous, we demonstrate true faith—trusting that the All-Knowing, All-Wise has better plans than our calculations."
  },
  29: {
    "Fight those who do not believe in Allah and the Last Day,": "This verse establishes the ruling for dealing with People of the Scripture (Jews and Christians) who become hostile to the Muslim state. It describes those who, despite having received earlier revelations, do not truly believe in Allah as He should be believed in, and do not properly believe in the Day of Judgment with its full implications. Their scriptures had been altered, leading to corrupted beliefs about God and the Hereafter.",
    "nor comply with what Allah and His Messenger have forbidden,": "They do not follow the divine prohibitions that were confirmed across all revelations—prohibitions that Allah's final Messenger also emphasized. This includes engaging in usury, consuming alcohol, and other forbidden practices that their original scriptures had prohibited but they had later permitted through distortions.",
    "nor embrace the religion of truth from among those who were given the Scripture,": "Despite having received previous scriptures (Torah, Gospel), they refuse to accept the final, complete religion of truth—Islam—which came to confirm and complete their own traditions. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was prophesied in their books, yet they rejected him. This refers specifically to those among Jews and Christians who oppose Islam despite knowing the truth.",
    "until they pay the tax, willingly submitting, fully humbled.": "The fighting is not endless—it has a resolution. If they do not accept Islam, they can live peacefully under Islamic governance by paying jizyah, a tax that exempts them from military service and provides them protection. The phrase 'willingly submitting' means they accept the political authority of the Islamic state. 'Fully humbled' means they acknowledge this arrangement respectfully, not arrogantly. Historically, jizyah was often less than what Muslims paid in zakah and military service obligations. This system allowed religious coexistence with clear terms, which was revolutionary for its time when religious minorities were often persecuted or expelled."
  },
  30: {
    "The Jews say, \"Ezra is the son of Allah,\"": "Some Jewish groups, particularly in Arabia during the Prophet's time, venerated Ezra (Uzair) to an extreme degree, elevating him to divine status. While not all Jews held this belief, some did, and Allah mentions it as an example of how People of the Scripture fell into exaggeration about righteous figures. Ezra was credited with restoring the Torah after the Babylonian exile, and some elevated him to superhuman status. This teaches us that exaggerating the status of any human, no matter how righteous, can lead to theological corruption.",
    "while the Christians say, \"The Messiah is the son of Allah.\"": "This is the mainstream Christian doctrine of Jesus being the literal Son of God, part of the Trinity. Islam categorically rejects this, affirming that Jesus (peace be upon him) was a mighty messenger of Allah, born miraculously to Virgin Mary, but not divine himself. He never claimed divinity; this belief developed after him. The Quran corrects this fundamental error while honoring Jesus as one of the greatest prophets.",
    "Such are their baseless assertions, only parroting the words of earlier disbelievers.": "These beliefs are not based on original revelation but on human fabrication, similar to how ancient pagan civilizations attributed sons and daughters to their gods. The Greeks, Romans, and others believed in divine offspring. Jews and Christians, influenced by surrounding cultures, incorporated similar ideas into their theology. They were 'parroting' pagan concepts while claiming to follow monotheistic scriptures—a tragic irony.",
    "May Allah condemn them! How can they be deluded ˹from the truth˺?": "This is a strong expression of divine displeasure at such beliefs. The question 'How can they be deluded?' expresses astonishment: how could people who received genuine revelation end up believing that God has children? God is the Creator, not a created being that reproduces. This fundamental confusion about God's nature is what makes these beliefs so serious."
  },
  31: {
    "They have taken their rabbis and monks as well as the Messiah, son of Mary, as lords besides Allah,": "When this verse was revealed, Adi ibn Hatim (a former Christian who embraced Islam) asked the Prophet (peace be upon him): 'We did not worship them.' The Prophet replied: 'Did they not make lawful for you what Allah had forbidden, and you considered it lawful? And did they not forbid for you what Allah had made lawful, and you considered it forbidden?' Adi said yes. The Prophet said: 'That is your worship of them' (Tirmidhi). This profound hadith explains that following religious leaders in making halal what Allah made haram (or vice versa) is a form of taking them as lords. It's not prostrating to them but giving them authority that belongs only to Allah.",
    "even though they were commanded to worship none but One God.": "Their original scriptures—the Torah and the Gospel in their uncorrupted forms—commanded pure monotheism. Moses (peace be upon him) taught: 'Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is One.' Jesus (peace be upon him) affirmed this. Yet their followers deviated into worshipping others besides Allah, whether through literal worship or through granting legislative authority that belongs only to God.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him.": "This is the fundamental message of all prophets: La ilaha illallah—there is no deity worthy of worship except Allah. All prophets, from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all), brought this same core message. Any religion that teaches otherwise has deviated from the prophetic way.",
    "Glorified is He above what they associate ˹with Him˺!": "Allah is far above and free from the partners they assign to Him—whether sons, daughters, saints with divine powers, or clergy with divine authority. This phrase (Subhanahu) expresses Allah's absolute transcendence and perfection, completely removed from any deficiency or need for partners or offspring."
  },
  32: {
    "They wish to extinguish Allah's light with their mouths,": "The enemies of Islam try to put out its truth through propaganda, lies, mockery, and distortion. The metaphor of extinguishing light with mouths is powerful—imagine someone trying to blow out the sun. No matter how hard they blow, the sun keeps shining. Similarly, no amount of human speech, false accusations, or propaganda campaigns can extinguish the truth of Islam. Throughout history, every generation has had those who predicted Islam's demise, yet it continues to grow and spread.",
    "but Allah will only allow His light to be perfected,": "Allah has decreed that His guidance—the Quran and the way of His final Messenger—will be preserved and completed. Unlike previous scriptures that were altered or lost, Islam's sources remain intact. The message continues to reach every corner of the earth. Allah Himself guarantees this, and no human effort can override divine will.",
    "even to the dismay of the disbelievers.": "Those who oppose Islam will be frustrated. Their efforts will fail. This doesn't mean they won't try or that Muslims won't face challenges, but the ultimate outcome is guaranteed. This gives believers confidence during difficult times—even when Islam seems weak or under attack, Allah's plan will prevail. History has repeatedly demonstrated this: from the persecution in Mecca to the Crusades to modern challenges, Islam has not only survived but spread."
  },
  33: {
    "He is the One Who has sent His Messenger with ˹true˺ guidance and the religion of truth,": "Allah sent Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) with two things: guidance (clear direction for how to live) and the religion of truth (the correct beliefs about God, the universe, and human purpose). This combination of knowledge and practice makes Islam complete—it tells you what to believe and how to act.",
    "making it prevail over all others,": "Islam will become dominant over all other religions and ideologies. This doesn't necessarily mean every person will become Muslim, but that Islam's truth will be evident, its arguments will be superior, and its influence will be undeniable. In some interpretations, this complete prevalence will happen when Jesus (peace be upon him) returns. In the meantime, Islam continues to spread as the fastest-growing religion despite all opposition.",
    "even to the dismay of the polytheists.": "Those who associate partners with Allah—whether ancient idol worshippers or modern forms of shirk—will be dismayed to see Islam's success. Their displeasure doesn't change the divine decree. This phrase encourages believers to continue their work regardless of opposition, knowing that success is promised by Allah Himself."
  },
  34: {
    "O believers! Indeed, many rabbis and monks consume people's wealth wrongfully": "Allah warns Muslims about a corrupt practice among religious leaders of previous nations. Note that Allah says 'many,' not 'all'—there were and are sincere religious figures, but many exploited their positions. They took money through selling religious rulings, accepting bribes to declare forbidden things permissible, charging for prayers and blessings, and manipulating people's religious sentiments for profit. This is a warning for Muslim scholars too—using religious knowledge for worldly gain is severely condemned.",
    "and hinder ˹others˺ from the Way of Allah.": "Beyond personal corruption, they blocked people from true guidance. They concealed prophecies about the final Prophet, distorted scriptures, and kept people in ignorance to maintain their power. A corrupt religious leader does double damage: they sin themselves and prevent others from finding the truth. This is why scholars have such heavy responsibility in Islam.",
    "Give good news of a painful torment to those who hoard gold and silver and do not spend it in Allah's cause.": "The verse now expands beyond religious leaders to anyone who hoards wealth without spending it properly. The sarcastic phrase 'give good news' emphasizes the certainty and severity of punishment. In Islamic economics, wealth must circulate—through zakah, charity, investment, and supporting good causes. Hoarding is prohibited because it harms the economy and indicates a heart attached to worldly possessions. This doesn't prohibit saving; it prohibits hoarding without paying obligatory dues and without benefiting others."
  },
  35: {
    "The Day ˹will come˺ when their treasure will be heated up in the Fire of Hell, and their foreheads, sides, and backs branded with it.": "This vivid description shows the punishment for hoarding: the very wealth they loved and protected will become instruments of torture. It will be heated in Hellfire and used to brand their bodies. The foreheads, sides, and backs are mentioned—perhaps because they turned their faces away from the needy, turned their sides when asked for help, and turned their backs on divine obligations. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Whoever is given wealth by Allah and does not pay its zakah, on the Day of Judgment it will appear as a bald-headed poisonous snake with two black spots over its eyes, coiling around his neck and biting his cheeks saying, \"I am your wealth, I am your treasure\"' (Bukhari).",
    "˹It will be said to them,˺ \"This is the treasure you hoarded for yourselves.": "They thought they were saving for their future, but their treasure became their punishment. The wealth they refused to share in this world follows them into the next—not as comfort but as torment. There's bitter irony here: they hoarded 'for themselves,' and now they receive it 'for themselves' in the most painful way.",
    "Now taste what you hoarded!\"": "The word 'taste' is used throughout the Quran for experiencing punishment. Just as one tastes food and experiences its flavor fully, they will fully experience the consequences of their greed. Every dirham they refused to give in charity, every poor person they ignored, every obligation they avoided—all of it returns. This should motivate believers to be generous and pay their zakah promptly."
  },
  36: {
    "Indeed, the number of months ordained by Allah is twelve—in Allah's Record since the day He created the heavens and the earth—": "The twelve-month lunar calendar is not a human invention but a divine ordinance established at creation. Allah set the movements of the sun and moon to create this time system. This emphasizes that some religious matters are fixed by Allah and cannot be changed by human consensus or convenience. The lunar calendar is part of Allah's cosmic order.",
    "of which four are sacred.": "Four months have special sanctity: Dhul-Qa'dah, Dhul-Hijjah, Muharram, and Rajab. Three are consecutive (related to Hajj) and one stands alone. During these months, fighting was historically prohibited, allowing safe travel for pilgrimage and trade. These months were recognized even in pre-Islamic Arabia as sacred, a remnant of Ibrahim's (peace be upon him) teachings.",
    "That is the Right Way.": "This system of sacred months is the correct, upright religion. Respecting these months is part of following the true faith. It's not cultural tradition but divine law.",
    "So do not wrong one another during these months.": "While wrongdoing is always prohibited, it's especially severe during sacred months. Sins committed in sacred times and places carry greater weight. This teaches consciousness of time—some moments are more spiritually significant than others, requiring extra vigilance.",
    "And together fight the polytheists as they fight against you together. And know that Allah is with those mindful ˹of Him˺.": "While the sacred months have special rules, if polytheists attack during them, Muslims can defend themselves. The enemy fights as a united force, so Muslims should also unite. But the key is maintaining taqwa (God-consciousness)—fighting with restraint, following divine rules even in war. Allah's support is with those who are mindful of Him, not just those with larger armies."
  },
  37: {
    "Reallocating the sanctity of ˹these˺ months is an increase in disbelief,": "The pre-Islamic Arabs practiced 'nasi''—postponing or switching the sacred months to suit their convenience. If they wanted to fight during a sacred month, they would declare it non-sacred and make another month sacred instead. This manipulation of divine law is called 'an increase in disbelief' because it involves changing Allah's decrees based on human desires—a form of playing God.",
    "by which the disbelievers are led ˹far˺ astray.": "This practice wasn't just wrong in itself; it led people further from truth. Each manipulation made the next one easier, and religious law became a tool for political convenience rather than divine guidance. This gradual corruption led to deeper misguidance.",
    "They adjust the sanctity one year and uphold it in another, only to maintain the number of months sanctified by Allah,": "They were clever about it—they kept the total number of sacred months at four to appear compliant with tradition. But they shuffled which months were sacred based on their needs. It looked religious on the surface while being manipulation underneath. This is a warning about maintaining the form of religion while violating its spirit.",
    "violating the very months Allah has made sacred.": "Despite their calculations, they were directly violating Allah's specific designations. Allah made particular months sacred, not just a quantity of months. The specific timing matters because Hajj and other rituals are connected to these exact months.",
    "Their evil deeds have been made appealing to them. And Allah does not guide the disbelieving people.": "They saw their manipulation as wise and practical. When people persist in sin, they start seeing it as reasonable and even good. This is a spiritual disease—when wrong starts looking right. Allah withdraws guidance from those who persistently choose disbelief, leaving them in their self-created darkness."
  },
  38: {
    "O believers! What is the matter with you that when you are asked to march forth in the cause of Allah, you cling firmly to ˹your˺ land?": "This verse was revealed regarding the Expedition of Tabuk in the 9th year after Hijrah. The Prophet (peace be upon him) called for a military expedition against the Byzantine Empire during extremely hot summer weather, when dates were ripening and shade was beloved. Some believers were reluctant to leave their comfortable lives. The phrase 'cling firmly to land' depicts someone so attached to their home, farm, and comfort that they become heavy and immovable. Allah questions this reluctance—what's wrong with you that comfort has become more important than Allah's cause?",
    "Do you prefer the life of this world over the Hereafter?": "This gets to the heart of the matter. Choosing comfort over sacrifice for Allah's cause is essentially choosing this temporary world over eternal Paradise. Every believer faces this choice repeatedly—when prayer time conflicts with sleep, when zakah competes with desires for luxury, when speaking truth might cost friendships. Which do we choose?",
    "The enjoyment of this worldly life is insignificant compared to that of the Hereafter.": "Even if you enjoyed every pleasure this world offers—and no one does—it would be like a drop compared to the ocean of the Hereafter's duration and quality. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'The world compared to the Hereafter is like one of you dipping his finger in the sea—let him see what he brings back' (Muslim). That wet fingertip is all of this world's pleasures compared to the Hereafter. Knowing this, why would anyone trade eternal bliss for temporary comfort?"
  },
  39: {
    "If you do not march forth, He will afflict you with a painful torment": "This is a serious warning. Refusing to respond to Allah's call when able is a major sin deserving punishment. The punishment could come in this world—military defeat, loss of blessings, humiliation—or in the Hereafter, or both. When believers have the ability to support Allah's cause and choose not to, there are consequences.",
    "and replace you with other people.": "If this community fails to fulfill its duty, Allah will bring another people who will. This has happened throughout history—nations that abandoned their covenant with Allah were replaced by others who took up the responsibility. The Arabs were not the first recipients of divine guidance; they became its carriers after previous nations failed. And if they fail, others will rise. This is both warning and humbling—no nation is indispensable to Allah's plan.",
    "You are not harming Him in the least.": "If believers refuse to strive, they harm only themselves. Allah is not affected by human disobedience. His kingdom continues, His plan unfolds, His religion spreads—with or without any particular individual or nation. The work will continue; the only question is whether you will be part of it or replaced.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "Allah has unlimited power to accomplish His will, to punish the disobedient, and to replace the negligent. His plans cannot be frustrated. This should inspire both hope and healthy fear—hope that His cause will triumph, and fear of being discarded for failing to participate."
  },
  40: {
    "˹It does not matter˺ if you ˹believers˺ do not support him, for Allah did in fact support him": "This is a powerful reminder: the Prophet (peace be upon him) doesn't need any human's help for his mission to succeed. Allah is sufficient. The believers' support benefits themselves, not the Prophet. This was demonstrated at the most vulnerable moment of his life.",
    "when the disbelievers drove him out ˹of Mecca˺ and he was only one of two.": "The Hijrah (migration to Medina) occurred when the Quraysh plotted to assassinate the Prophet. He left Mecca secretly with only Abu Bakr (may Allah be pleased with him) as his companion. Two men against the entire Qurayshi search party—humanly impossible odds. Yet this was when Allah's help was most evident.",
    "While they both were in the cave, he reassured his companion, \"Do not worry; Allah is certainly with us.\"": "They hid in the Cave of Thawr for three days. The Quraysh trackers came so close that Abu Bakr could see their feet at the cave entrance. He whispered fearfully to the Prophet, 'If any of them looks down at his feet, he will see us!' The Prophet's response was not human confidence but divine certainty: 'Do not worry; Allah is certainly with us.' A spider had spun a web over the entrance, and a dove had nested there—signs that no one had entered recently. The trackers left without looking inside.",
    "So Allah sent down His serenity upon the Prophet, supported him with forces you ˹believers˺ did not see,": "Divine tranquility (sakinah) descended on the Prophet, and invisible forces protected them. Whether angels, or the spider and dove, or simply turning the enemies' attention away—Allah protected His Messenger through means both seen and unseen.",
    "and made the word of the disbelievers lowest, while the Word of Allah is supreme.": "The Quraysh's plans failed completely. Their 'word' (their plots, their religion, their dominance) was brought low, while Islam spread throughout Arabia and beyond. Within decades, the very people hunting the Prophet were either Muslim or living under Muslim governance. Allah's Word—His religion, His guidance—prevailed as promised.",
    "And Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah has absolute power and perfect wisdom. His plan at Thawr seemed like abandonment—two men hiding in a cave from powerful enemies. But it was perfect wisdom: this moment of apparent weakness became the foundation for unstoppable success. The Hijrah marks the beginning of the Islamic calendar, the turning point of history."
  },
  41: {
    "˹O believers!˺ March forth whether it is easy or difficult for you,": "After reminding believers of Allah's support for the Prophet, comes the command to march forth regardless of circumstances. 'Easy or difficult' encompasses all situations: whether you're young or old, wealthy or poor, equipped or under-equipped, in good health or facing challenges. There's no acceptable excuse for abandoning the community's collective obligation when called.",
    "and strive with your wealth and your lives in the cause of Allah.": "Jihad involves both financial sacrifice and personal effort. Some support the cause with money—equipping soldiers, helping families of those who march, funding logistics. Others give their time and physical presence. Both are forms of striving. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Fight the polytheists with your wealth, your lives, and your tongues' (Abu Dawud). Everyone has something to contribute.",
    "That is best for you, if only you knew.": "This sacrifice—which seems like loss—is actually the best thing for you. It purifies the soul, earns enormous rewards, protects the community, and leads to Allah's pleasure. If believers truly understood the value of what they gain versus what they temporarily give up, they would rush to participate. The phrase 'if only you knew' suggests that ignorance, not logic, makes people reluctant."
  },
  42: {
    "Had the gain been within reach and the journey shorter, they would have followed you,": "Allah exposes the hypocrites' true motivations. If there had been easy money to gain and a short, comfortable journey, they would have been eager to join. Their issue wasn't inability but unwillingness when no worldly benefit was visible. They were willing to 'serve Islam' when it served them—a classic sign of hypocrisy.",
    "but the distance seemed too long for them.": "The Expedition of Tabuk required traveling approximately 700 kilometers in scorching summer heat to confront the Byzantine Empire—the superpower of the time. This was genuinely difficult. But for true believers, difficulty doesn't prevent obedience; it makes it more valuable. For hypocrites, any significant difficulty reveals their true nature.",
    "And they will swear by Allah, \"Had we been able, we would have certainly joined you.\"": "When the army returned, these hypocrites would take oaths by Allah that they wanted to go but couldn't. They would cite health problems, family emergencies, financial constraints—anything to appear faithful while having been cowardly. Using Allah's name for false oaths compounds their sin.",
    "They are ruining themselves. And Allah knows that they are surely lying.": "Their lies destroy their own souls. They think they're clever, but they're only accumulating sin. And Allah—who knows all hidden things—knows they're lying. Their excuses might fool people, but they never fool Allah. This is terrifying for hypocrites and reassuring for sincere believers: all things will be revealed."
  },
  43: {
    "May Allah pardon you ˹O Prophet˺!": "This phrase indicates Allah's love and honor for the Prophet (peace be upon him)—beginning with pardon before even mentioning what needs pardoning. Some scholars say this style is used to soften what follows, showing divine gentleness. The Prophet, being human, made judgments based on what people told him.",
    "Why did you give them permission ˹to stay behind˺ before those who told the truth were distinguished from those who were lying?": "When hypocrites came with excuses, the Prophet (peace be upon him) accepted their word and excused them from the expedition. Allah gently indicates it would have been better to wait—let them either join the army (proving sincerity) or refuse without excuse (exposing hypocrisy). By accepting excuses quickly, the hypocrites maintained their cover. This teaches leaders to be discerning and not accept claims too readily when the stakes are high. However, this was a judgment call, not a sin, which is why Allah begins with pardon."
  },
  44: {
    "Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day do not ask for exemption from striving with their wealth and their lives.": "True believers don't look for ways out of serving Allah's cause. When called, they respond. They don't make excuses, seek exemptions, or try to avoid difficulty. Their faith in Allah and awareness of the Hereafter motivates them to sacrifice now for eternal reward later. This is a diagnostic criterion: someone constantly seeking exemptions from Islamic obligations likely has weak faith.",
    "And Allah has perfect knowledge of those who are mindful ˹of Him˺.": "Allah knows who truly has taqwa—who genuinely fears Him and hopes in Him. External appearance might deceive people, but Allah sees hearts. This is comforting for sincere believers whose efforts might go unrecognized by people, and terrifying for those who put on shows of piety while their hearts are empty."
  },
  45: {
    "No one would ask for exemption except those who have no faith in Allah or the Last Day,": "This verse clearly states that seeking exemption (when able) indicates lack of faith. Someone who truly believes Allah is watching and the Day of Judgment is coming would never try to avoid obligations. The desire to be exempted reveals what the heart truly believes—or doesn't believe.",
    "and whose hearts are in doubt, so they are torn by their doubts.": "Hypocrites are characterized by doubt—they're not sure if Islam is true, if the Hereafter is real, if Allah really sees everything. This doubt makes them hesitant, wavering, unable to commit. They're 'torn'—pulled between pretending to be Muslim (for social acceptance) and avoiding the sacrifices real faith requires. This internal conflict is itself a punishment—they have neither the peace of believers nor the freedom of open disbelievers."
  },
  46: {
    "Had they ˹really˺ intended to march forth, they would have made preparations for it.": "True intention shows in action. If someone genuinely wants to do something, they prepare. The hypocrites claimed they wanted to join but had no supplies, animals, or equipment ready. Their lack of preparation exposed their lack of intention. This principle applies broadly: if someone truly intends to pray Fajr, they set an alarm; if they intend to give charity, they set aside money. Unprepared people reveal uncommitted hearts.",
    "But Allah disliked that they should go, so He let them lag behind,": "Here's a profound insight: Allah actually didn't want these hypocrites in the army. Their presence would have caused more harm than good. So He made them feel lazy, put barriers in their way, and facilitated their staying behind. Sometimes when someone faces obstacles in doing a 'good' deed, it might be Allah protecting the cause from their corrupt influence. Allah's wisdom operates on levels we don't always understand.",
    "and it was said ˹to them˺, \"Stay with those ˹helpless˺ who remain behind.\"": "They were effectively told: 'Just stay home with the women, children, elderly, and sick who have legitimate reasons not to fight.' This was deeply humiliating for Arab men who prized their warrior reputation. Being grouped with non-combatants was shameful. But this was their deserved status—they had the bodies of men but not the courage of believers."
  },
  47: {
    "Had they gone forth with you ˹believers˺, they would have been nothing but trouble for you,": "Allah explains why their absence was actually beneficial. These hypocrites would have caused chaos, confusion, and problems within the ranks. Military operations require unity and trust; having unreliable elements creates vulnerability. Their presence would have subtracted from, not added to, the army's strength.",
    "and would have scrambled around, seeking to spread discord in your midst.": "They would have moved among the soldiers spreading rumors, doubts, fear, and discouragement. 'The enemy is too strong,' 'This mission is suicide,' 'Why are we even here?'—this kind of talk destroys morale. Hypocrites specialize in fitna (discord); keeping them away protected the believers from their poison.",
    "And some of you would have eagerly listened to them.": "Not everyone would recognize the hypocrites' manipulation. Some sincere but naive believers would have been influenced, their confidence shaken, their resolve weakened. This is why Allah didn't just expose the hypocrites but actually kept them away—to protect vulnerable believers from being affected by their negativity.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of the wrongdoers.": "Allah knows exactly who the troublemakers are, what they planned, and what damage they would have caused. His keeping them behind was not chance but precise wisdom. He knows the wrongdoers thoroughly—their identities, their techniques, and their impact—and He protects His sincere servants from them."
  },
  48: {
    "They had already sought to spread discord before": "This wasn't their first attempt at sabotage. Throughout the Prophet's mission in Medina, hypocrites had tried to create divisions, spread rumors, and undermine the Muslim community. At Uhud, they withdrew one-third of the army. During various crises, they worked to cause panic. Their history proved their character.",
    "and devised every ˹possible˺ plot against you ˹O Prophet˺,": "They schemed, planned, and tried everything to bring down the Prophet's mission—political manipulation, social disruption, spreading lies, coordinating with external enemies. They were not passive skeptics but active adversaries working from within.",
    "until the truth came and Allah's Will prevailed—much to their dismay.": "Despite all their plots, Islam continued to grow, victories continued to come, and Allah's plan unfolded. The conquest of Mecca, the defeat of hostile tribes, the spreading of Islam—all happened while hypocrites watched in frustration. Their displeasure confirmed they were on the wrong side. When truth triumphs, hypocrites are miserable; when Muslims face difficulty, hypocrites are happy. Their emotional reactions expose their reality."
  },
  49: {
    "There are some of them who say, \"Exempt me and do not expose me to temptation.\"": "One hypocrite, al-Jadd ibn Qays, asked to be excused from the Tabuk expedition claiming he would be tempted by the Byzantine women and couldn't control himself. He portrayed this as piety—avoiding sin. But it was actually cowardice dressed up as religious concern. This type of excuse uses religious language to avoid religious duty. It's a sophisticated form of hypocrisy.",
    "They have already fallen into temptation.": "Allah exposes the irony: while claiming to avoid temptation, they've fallen into the greatest temptation of all—disobeying Allah's command and abandoning His cause. They worried about the minor 'fitna' of attraction to women while committing the major fitna of betraying their faith. They avoided a theoretical sin while committing an actual one.",
    "And Hell will surely engulf the disbelievers.": "Their clever excuse won't save them from Hellfire. No matter how religious their reasoning sounds, if they're avoiding what Allah commanded, they're moving toward Hell, not away from it. Hell will surround them completely—'encompass' them—leaving no escape. The word choice emphasizes totality of punishment for those who reject faith while pretending to be believers."
  },
  50: {
    "If a blessing befalls you ˹O Prophet˺, they grieve,": "When Muslims achieved victory, gained wealth, or experienced any success, hypocrites were sad. Their outer expression might be neutral, but inside they grieved. A believer would rejoice at the Prophet's success; their grief exposed their inner enmity. Jealousy of Muslims' success is a sign of diseased hearts.",
    "but if a disaster befalls you, they say, \"We took our precaution in advance,\"": "When Muslims faced setbacks, hypocrites congratulated themselves on their 'wisdom' in staying behind. 'See? We knew this would fail!' They felt vindicated, proud of their cowardice, and relieved they weren't affected. This self-congratulation during others' hardship reveals cruel, selfish hearts.",
    "and turn away, rejoicing.": "They physically and emotionally distance themselves from the Muslim community during difficulty, feeling happy about the believers' troubles. True believers share in each other's joys and sorrows; hypocrites rejoice at believers' sorrows and grieve at their joys. Their emotional responses are completely inverted from what they should be."
  },
  51: {
    "Say, \"Nothing will ever befall us except what Allah has destined for us.": "The Prophet is commanded to respond with the perspective of true faith. Everything—good or bad—is by Allah's decree. Victory or defeat, ease or hardship, life or death—all are written. This belief brings peace: there's no random chaos, no cruel fate, only Allah's wise plan. Muslims accept whatever comes, knowing it's from their Lord.",
    "He is our Protector.\"": "Allah is our Mawla—our protector, guardian, helper, and supporter. This relationship changes everything. When the Lord of the Universe is protecting you, what can any enemy do? The hypocrites have no such protector; their worldly precautions give them only an illusion of safety.",
    "So in Allah let the believers put their trust.": "Tawakkul (trust in Allah) is the believer's response to uncertainty. We take reasonable precautions (as the Prophet did), but ultimate trust is in Allah, not in our preparations. This trust brings freedom from anxiety, courage in danger, and patience in hardship. Hypocrites trust themselves and their calculations; believers trust Allah."
  },
  52: {
    "Say, \"Are you awaiting anything to befall us except one of the two best things: ˹victory or martyrdom˺?": "This is a powerful reframe. The hypocrites wait to see what happens to the believers, hoping for their misfortune. But the Prophet is commanded to point out: what are you waiting for exactly? If Muslims win, that's excellent. If Muslims die fighting, that's martyrdom—also excellent! Either outcome is a 'husna' (good thing) for believers. The worst-case scenario from a worldly perspective (death) is actually the best-case scenario spiritually (Paradise). How can you wait to see us 'fail' when we can only win?",
    "But We are awaiting Allah to afflict you with torment either from Him or at our hands.": "Now the tables turn. While hypocrites wait for Muslims to suffer, Muslims are waiting for hypocrites' punishment—either divine punishment directly from Allah (disease, disaster, death) or punishment through believers' hands (exposure, defeat, execution for treason). The hypocrites' future holds only variations of suffering.",
    "So keep waiting! We too are waiting with you.\"": "This challenging conclusion puts the two groups on equal footing—both waiting—but with vastly different prospects. Muslims wait for their guaranteed good outcome; hypocrites wait for their guaranteed punishment. The sarcasm is evident: 'Go ahead and wait. We're waiting too. Let's see who ends up happier.' This confidence comes from faith—knowing the ultimate outcomes are already determined by Allah in favor of truth."
  },
  53: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"˹Whether you˺ donate willingly or unwillingly,": "The Prophet is commanded to deliver a stark message to the hypocrites. Whether they give charity eagerly or reluctantly, whether they make a show of generosity or give grudgingly—it makes no difference. The manner of giving, whether enthusiastic or forced, doesn't change the outcome for them.",
    "it will never be accepted from you,": "Their charitable deeds will be rejected by Allah. This is devastating news for anyone who thinks good deeds automatically earn reward. The reality is that deeds are judged not just by their appearance but by the faith behind them. A magnificent donation from a heart devoid of faith is worthless in Allah's sight, while a small sincere offering from a believing heart is treasured.",
    "for you have been a rebellious people.\"": "The reason for rejection is clear: they are fasiqun—people who have stepped outside the boundaries of faith and obedience. Their rebellion against Allah and His Messenger has nullified any good they might do. This is like an employee who betrays their company trying to earn a bonus—no matter how much extra work they do, their fundamental disloyalty disqualifies them. The term 'rebellious' encompasses their rejection of faith, their opposition to the Prophet, and their consistent violation of divine commands."
  },
  54: {
    "And what prevented their donations from being accepted is that they have lost faith in Allah and His Messenger,": "Allah now elaborates on why their charity is rejected. The fundamental reason is disbelief—they don't truly believe in Allah or accept Muhammad (peace be upon him) as His Messenger. Without this foundation, all religious acts crumble. Faith is the soil in which good deeds grow; without it, nothing takes root. Their outward Muslim identity is a facade covering inner rejection.",
    "they never come to prayer except half-heartedly,": "Their prayer—the most important act of worship—reveals their hypocrisy. They come to prayer lazily, reluctantly, viewing it as a burden rather than a gift. True believers rush to prayer eagerly, finding peace and joy in it. Hypocrites drag themselves there only to be seen, only to maintain appearances. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that the heaviest prayer for hypocrites is Isha and Fajr—prayers in darkness when no one sees them coming to the mosque (Bukhari and Muslim). Their laziness in prayer exposes their spiritual emptiness.",
    "and they never donate except resentfully.": "When they do give charity, it's with resentment and bitterness. They see it as a loss, not an investment in the Hereafter. They might give to avoid suspicion or to gain social standing, but inside they hate parting with their money. True believers give joyfully, knowing that what they spend for Allah's sake is actually saved for them. The hypocrites' resentful giving shows they don't believe in divine reward and consider charity a waste."
  },
  55: {
    "So let neither their wealth nor children impress you ˹O Prophet˺.": "Don't be deceived by the hypocrites' worldly success. They might have impressive wealth, successful businesses, many children, and comfortable lives. On the surface, it looks like they're blessed. But appearances are misleading. This verse corrects a common misconception: worldly prosperity is not a sign of Allah's pleasure. Sometimes it's the opposite.",
    "Allah only intends to torment them through these things in this worldly life,": "Their wealth and children—things that should bring happiness—actually become sources of suffering. The wealth brings anxiety about losing it, exhaustion in maintaining it, and prevents them from focusing on what truly matters. Their children may cause them grief, disappointment, or conflict. What looks like blessing is actually punishment in disguise. They work tirelessly for things that give them no lasting satisfaction.",
    "then their souls will depart while they are disbelievers.": "The ultimate tragedy: after a life of accumulating and worrying, they die in a state of disbelief. All their wealth stays behind; only their empty souls proceed to judgment. They spent their lives collecting what they couldn't keep and neglecting what they couldn't lose (their faith and good deeds). The phrase emphasizes the horror of dying without faith—the moment when reality becomes clear but it's too late to change."
  },
  56: {
    "They swear by Allah that they are part of you,": "The hypocrites take oaths by Allah Himself, claiming to be genuine members of the Muslim community. They use Allah's name—the most sacred oath possible—to convince believers of their sincerity. They say 'We are with you, we are one of you, we share your faith and your struggle.' Their oaths sound convincing because they invoke the divine.",
    "but they are not.": "Allah exposes the truth: despite their oaths, they are not part of the believing community. Their bodies may be present in the mosque and their names on the register, but their hearts belong elsewhere. Physical presence and verbal claims do not make someone a believer. True belonging to the Muslim community requires genuine faith, and that they lack entirely.",
    "They only say so out of fear.": "The motivation behind their false oaths is fear—fear of being exposed, fear of losing social position, fear of consequences if Muslims discovered their true beliefs. It's not love for Islam or conviction in its truth that makes them claim membership; it's terror of what would happen if they were honest. This fear-based 'faith' is worthless. It produces only lies and eventually leads to their disgrace when Allah exposes them."
  },
  57: {
    "If only they could find a refuge, or a cave, or any hiding-place,": "Allah reveals their true desire: they desperately want to escape from the Muslim community. A refuge (a fortified place), a cave (a natural hiding spot), or any hole to crawl into—anything that would let them leave without consequences. They stay among Muslims only because they have nowhere else to go safely.",
    "they would rush headlong towards it.": "The word 'rush headlong' (yajmahun) describes a horse running wildly, out of control, bolting toward something. This is how desperately they want to escape. They're not casually considering leaving; they would sprint away if given the chance. Their presence in the Muslim community is not choice but circumstance. This vivid image of panicked flight reveals how much they hate being among believers and how insincere their claims of belonging truly are."
  },
  58: {
    "There are some of them who are critical of your distribution of alms ˹O Prophet˺.": "Some hypocrites criticized how the Prophet (peace be upon him) distributed zakah and charity funds. They complained that he was unfair, gave too much to some people and too little to others, or showed favoritism. This criticism of the Prophet's divinely-guided decisions reveals their arrogance—they thought they knew better than Allah's Messenger how resources should be allocated.",
    "If they are given some of it they are pleased,": "When they received a share of the charity, suddenly they had no complaints. The distribution was fine, the Prophet was just, everything was wonderful. Their satisfaction depended entirely on whether they personally benefited. This exposes their motivation: not concern for fairness or the poor, but pure self-interest.",
    "but if not they are enraged.": "When they didn't get what they wanted, they became furious. Their anger showed they viewed charity as their right, as something owed to them, not as a blessing for the genuinely needy. True believers are content whether they receive or not, trusting that Allah and His Messenger distribute justly. Hypocrites make their pleasure or anger dependent on personal gain—a clear sign of corrupt hearts."
  },
  59: {
    "If only they had been content with what Allah and His Messenger had given them": "Allah describes the correct attitude they should have had. Whether they received much, little, or nothing from the charity distribution, they should have been satisfied, trusting that Allah and His Messenger know best. Contentment (rida) is a key quality of believers—accepting what comes from Allah without complaint.",
    "and said, \"Allah is sufficient for us!": "The proper response is to declare Allah's sufficiency. If you have Him, you have everything you need. He is the ultimate provider, and His plans are perfect. This declaration (hasbunallah) is one of the most powerful statements of faith—it was the response of Ibrahim (peace be upon him) when thrown into fire and of the believers when threatened by enemies (Surah Al-Imran 3:173).",
    "Allah will grant us out of His bounty, and so will His Messenger.": "Instead of complaining about what they didn't receive, they should have maintained hope in future provision. Allah's bounty is unlimited; if not now, then later. If not through this channel, then through another. The Prophet (peace be upon him) was also a means of provision for the community. This optimism reflects true faith—trusting that Allah's provision will come.",
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ we turn with hope.\"": "All hopes and desires should be directed to Allah. When we need something, we ask Him. When we're disappointed, we trust His wisdom. When we hope for better, we hope in His bounty. Turning to Allah with hope (raghbah) means He is our ultimate refuge and source. This attitude would have saved the hypocrites from their misery of constant dissatisfaction."
  },
  60: {
    "Alms-tax is only for the poor": "The first category is al-fuqara (the poor)—those who lack basic necessities and cannot meet their essential needs. They have little or nothing and struggle to survive. Zakah provides them with direct financial support to cover food, clothing, shelter, and other necessities.",
    "and the needy,": "The second category is al-masakin (the needy)—those who have some income but not enough to fully meet their needs. They might have a job or some resources but still fall short of a decent standard of living. The distinction between poor and needy is subtle: the poor have nothing, while the needy have something but not enough.",
    "for those employed to administer it,": "The third category is zakah workers—those appointed to collect, manage, and distribute zakah funds. They receive payment for their work from zakah itself, even if they're not personally poor. This ensures the zakah system functions efficiently with dedicated staff.",
    "for those whose hearts are attracted ˹to the faith˺,": "The fourth category is those whose hearts are being reconciled to Islam (al-mu'allafah qulubuhum). This includes new Muslims who need support as they adjust, or non-Muslims whose goodwill toward Islam is valuable to the community. Some scholars include those who might be inclined to accept Islam if shown generosity.",
    "for ˹freeing˺ slaves,": "The fifth category is freeing those in bondage (fi'r-riqab). This could mean helping slaves purchase their freedom, paying for captives' release, or in modern interpretation, liberating those trapped in any form of bondage. Islam systematically worked to eliminate slavery partly through this zakah category.",
    "for those in debt,": "The sixth category is al-gharimin (the indebted)—those who have fallen into debt due to legitimate reasons and cannot repay. This helps them clear their obligations and regain their dignity. It doesn't include those who borrowed irresponsibly or for forbidden purposes.",
    "for Allah's cause,": "The seventh category is fi sabilillah (in Allah's cause)—traditionally understood as supporting those fighting to defend Islam, but scholars also include other religious causes like Islamic education, da'wah, building mosques, and other community needs that serve Islam.",
    "and for ˹needy˺ travellers.": "The eighth category is ibn as-sabil (the wayfarer)—travelers who are stranded or in need, even if they're wealthy back home. Anyone stuck in a foreign place without access to their resources can receive zakah to help them complete their journey.",
    "˹This is˺ an obligation from Allah.": "These eight categories are not suggestions but divine obligations. Zakah must go to these recipients, not to other causes however worthy they might seem. This is Allah's law, not subject to human modification.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "Allah knows the needs of society and the wisdom behind each category. The zakah system addresses poverty, converts' needs, freedom, debt, community defense, and traveler assistance—a comprehensive social welfare system designed by the All-Knowing, All-Wise Creator."
  },
  61: {
    "And there are others who hurt the Prophet by saying, \"He listens to anyone.\"": "Some hypocrites mocked the Prophet (peace be upon him) by calling him an 'ear' (udhun)—meaning he listens to whatever anyone tells him, is too gullible, believes every story. They said this critically, implying he was naive and easily manipulated. When he listened kindly to their excuses and accepted their explanations, they privately mocked his trusting nature.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"He listens to what is best for you.": "Allah commands the Prophet to respond by reframing the criticism. Yes, he is an 'ear'—but an ear for good! He listens to guidance from Allah, listens to the believers' concerns, listens to give people the benefit of the doubt. His listening nature is a mercy, not a weakness. He listens to what benefits the community.",
    "He believes in Allah,": "The Prophet's primary trust is in Allah. Whatever he hears from people, he measures against divine guidance. His belief in Allah protects him from being truly deceived about matters of faith and community welfare.",
    "has faith in the believers,": "He trusts the sincere believers. This trust is appropriate because believers deserve trust. He accepts their word because they're honest. If hypocrites exploit this trust, the sin is on them, not on him for being trusting.",
    "and is a mercy for those who believe among you.\"": "The Prophet's character—including his willingness to listen and trust—is a mercy for believers. His kindness, his accepting nature, his readiness to forgive makes the religion accessible and the community warm. Believers benefit from his merciful approach.",
    "Those who hurt Allah's Messenger will suffer a painful punishment.": "The verse ends with a severe warning. Mocking, criticizing, or hurting the Prophet in any way has serious consequences. Allah defends His Messenger's honor. Those who thought they were cleverly mocking him are actually earning painful punishment for themselves."
  },
  62: {
    "They swear by Allah to you ˹believers˺ in order to please you,": "The hypocrites take oaths to satisfy the believers, to keep them happy, to maintain their cover. Their focus is on making people pleased with them—saying whatever believers want to hear, swearing to convince them of sincerity.",
    "while it is the pleasure of Allah and His Messenger they should seek, if they are ˹true˺ believers.": "This exposes their inverted priorities. True believers seek Allah's pleasure first, then His Messenger's. Human approval is secondary or irrelevant compared to divine approval. The hypocrites have it backwards—they care about people's opinions and ignore Allah's. If they truly believed, they would prioritize pleasing Allah over pleasing the community. The singular form 'yurduhu' (please Him) is used, indicating that pleasing Allah and His Messenger are one unified goal—what pleases Allah pleases His Messenger."
  },
  63: {
    "Do they not know that whoever opposes Allah and His Messenger": "A rhetorical question highlighting their ignorance or willful blindness. 'Yuhadid' means to oppose, to be on the opposite side, to work against. Anyone who positions themselves against Allah and His Messenger has chosen to be an enemy of the Creator.",
    "will be in the Fire of Hell forever?": "The consequence of opposing Allah is eternal Hellfire. Not temporary punishment but forever—endless, without hope of release. This should terrify anyone considering opposition to divine commands.",
    "That is the ultimate disgrace.": "Beyond the physical torment, Hell represents complete humiliation. The hypocrites who sought people's approval while ignoring Allah's will face the ultimate shame—exposed before all of creation, punished eternally, their pretense stripped away. What could be more disgraceful than this ending?"
  },
  64: {
    "The hypocrites fear that a sûrah should be revealed about them, exposing what is in their hearts.": "Deep down, hypocrites feared that Allah would reveal their secrets. They knew the Quran came from Allah, and they knew Allah knew their hearts. Every new revelation made them nervous—would this one expose them? This fear is itself proof they knew the Quran was true; otherwise, why worry about what it might say?",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Keep mocking! Allah will definitely bring to light what you fear.\"": "The Prophet is commanded to challenge them: go ahead, continue your mockery, continue your secret meetings and whispered insults. Allah will expose everything you're trying to hide. This is both a warning and a prediction—and indeed, Surah At-Tawbah exposed hypocrites so thoroughly that it was called 'Al-Fadihah' (The Exposer) and 'Al-Mubaʿthirah' (The Scrutinizer)."
  },
  65: {
    "If you question them, they will certainly say, \"We were only talking idly and joking around.\"": "This refers to a specific incident during the Tabuk expedition. Some hypocrites were mocking the Prophet and the believers, saying things like 'These Quran-reciters of ours are the greediest, the biggest liars, and the most cowardly in battle.' When confronted, they tried to dismiss their words as harmless banter, just passing time, nothing serious.",
    "Say, \"Was it Allah, His revelations, and His Messenger that you ridiculed?\"": "The Prophet is commanded to expose the gravity of their 'jokes.' You claim you were just joking? About what? About Allah Himself? About the Quran—His divine speech? About His Messenger? These are not subjects for humor. There is no such thing as harmless mockery of the sacred. What they thought was casual conversation was actually blasphemy."
  },
  66: {
    "Make no excuses! You have lost faith after your belief.": "Their excuses are rejected. By mocking Allah, His verses, and His Messenger, they have committed disbelief (kufr). Whatever faith they claimed to have is now void. This is a clear legal ruling: ridiculing sacred matters constitutes apostasy. They cannot claim 'it was just a joke' because such jokes reveal the heart's true condition.",
    "If We pardon a group of you,": "Allah indicates that some among those involved might be pardoned. Perhaps some were less involved, or were pressured by others, or showed genuine remorse and repented sincerely. Allah's door of mercy remains open even in severe situations.",
    "We will punish others for their wickedness.": "But those who led the mockery, who did so deliberately and persistently, who showed no remorse—they will be punished. Their criminality (ijram) earns them punishment. This distinguishes between degrees of guilt and shows that Allah judges each individual according to their specific actions and intentions."
  },
  67: {
    "The hypocrites, both men and women, are all alike:": "Male and female hypocrites share the same corrupt characteristics. They form one group united by their hypocrisy, reinforcing each other's disbelief. While believers are diverse in personality but united in faith, hypocrites are united in their spiritual disease.",
    "they encourage what is evil, forbid what is good,": "This is the exact opposite of believers who 'enjoin good and forbid evil.' Hypocrites promote wrongdoing—gossip, mockery, rebellion against Islamic values—while discouraging acts of faith and righteousness. They create an environment where sin seems acceptable and piety seems strange or extreme.",
    "and withhold ˹what is in˺ their hands.": "They are stingy, refusing to spend for good causes. Their fists are closed (qabadha)—a vivid image of tight-fistedness. They don't contribute to charity, community projects, or any sacrifice for Islam. Their wealth stays locked away while others' needs go unmet.",
    "They neglected Allah, so He neglected them.": "This is profound divine justice. They forgot about Allah—His rights, His commands, His watching over them—so Allah has abandoned them to their misguidance. He withdraws His guidance, His support, His mercy. They chose to ignore Him, so He leaves them in their darkness. This 'forgetting' by Allah means He treats them as if they don't matter, doesn't help them, doesn't guide them to repentance.",
    "Surely the hypocrites are the rebellious.": "The verdict is clear: hypocrites are fasiqun—transgressors who have stepped outside all bounds of faith and morality. They are the worst category of rebellious people because they combine disbelief with deception."
  },
  68: {
    "Allah has promised the hypocrites, both men and women, and the disbelievers an everlasting stay in the Fire of Hell—": "While Allah's promises to believers are of Paradise, His 'promise' to hypocrites and disbelievers is Hell. Note that hypocrites are mentioned first, emphasizing their particularly severe condition—they're even more dangerous than open disbelievers because they corrupt from within. Both groups face eternal punishment.",
    "it is sufficient for them.": "Hell is 'enough' for them—a grim statement meaning they've earned nothing else, nothing better. All their worldly efforts, wealth, and scheming result only in qualifying for Hellfire. It's sufficient punishment for their sufficient evil.",
    "Allah has condemned them,": "Allah's curse (la'nah) is upon them—they are expelled from His mercy, cut off from His grace. To be cursed by Allah is the worst possible state because it means divine abandonment.",
    "and they will suffer a never-ending punishment.": "The punishment is not temporary but permanent (muqim)—established, settled, constant. No parole, no relief, no end. This repetition of eternity emphasizes the horrific permanence of their fate."
  },
  69: {
    "˹You hypocrites are˺ like those ˹disbelievers˺ before you.": "The current hypocrites are following the exact pattern of destroyed nations before them. They're not original in their disbelief—they're repeating history, heading toward the same fate.",
    "They were far superior to you in might and more abundant in wealth and children.": "Previous nations—like 'Ad, Thamud, and Pharaoh's people—were much more powerful, wealthy, and numerous than these Arabian hypocrites. If greater power couldn't save those nations from Allah's punishment, what chance do these hypocrites have?",
    "They enjoyed their share in this life.": "Those nations had their portion (khalaq) of worldly enjoyment—their time of prosperity, pleasure, and power. They indulged fully in what this life offered.",
    "You have enjoyed your share, just as they did.": "Now these hypocrites are doing the same—enjoying their temporary portion of worldly life, thinking it will last, ignoring what comes after.",
    "And you have engaged in idle talk, just as they did.": "Like their predecessors, they spend their time in frivolous talk, mockery, and empty discourse instead of remembering Allah and preparing for the Hereafter. The word 'khawdh' implies plunging into falsehood and vain discussion.",
    "Their deeds have become void in this world and the Hereafter.": "All their achievements, constructions, and accomplishments amount to nothing. Their deeds are nullified—no benefit in this world (their civilizations destroyed) and no benefit in the Hereafter (no reward, only punishment).",
    "And it is they who are the ˹true˺ losers.": "Despite appearing successful by worldly standards, they are the ultimate losers. They lost everything that matters and gained only temporary pleasures followed by eternal pain."
  },
  70: {
    "Have they not received the stories of those ˹destroyed˺ before them:": "A rhetorical question challenging the hypocrites: haven't they heard what happened to previous nations? These stories were well-known among Arabs, some preserved in their traditions, others told through the Quran. Ignorance is no excuse.",
    "the people of Noah,": "The people of Nuh (peace be upon him) who rejected him for 950 years of preaching and were destroyed by the great flood—only those on the ark survived.",
    "'Âd,": "The mighty nation of 'Ad, people of the prophet Hud (peace be upon him), who were destroyed by a devastating wind that blew for seven nights and eight days.",
    "and Thamûd,": "The people of Thamud, who rejected prophet Salih (peace be upon him) and killed the miraculous she-camel, were destroyed by a blast (earthquake or thunderbolt).",
    "the people of Abraham,": "Those who rejected Ibrahim (peace be upon him), including Nimrod's kingdom. Nimrod himself was destroyed by a tiny mosquito that entered his brain.",
    "the residents of Midian,": "The people of Shu'ayb (peace be upon him) who cheated in their business dealings and were destroyed by earthquake and burning heat.",
    "and the overturned cities ˹of Lot˺?": "The cities of Sodom and Gomorrah, people of Lut (peace be upon him), who practiced homosexuality and were destroyed—their cities literally overturned (mu'tafikaat), with stones of brimstone raining down.",
    "Their messengers came to them with clear proofs.": "Each nation received messengers with clear evidence, miracles, and undeniable truth. They weren't destroyed arbitrarily—they had every opportunity to accept guidance.",
    "Allah would have never wronged them, but it was they who wronged themselves.": "Allah is perfectly just. He didn't wrong these nations—they wronged themselves through their rejection, arrogance, and persistence in sin. Their destruction was the natural consequence of their choices. This principle applies to the hypocrites: if punishment comes, it's not Allah's injustice but their own self-destruction."
  },
  71: {
    "The believers, both men and women, are guardians of one another.": "In beautiful contrast to hypocrites who are 'all alike' in evil, believers are 'awliya' (protectors, supporters, allies) of each other. This is a community of mutual care—men protecting women, women supporting men, each believer looking out for others. This creates brotherhood and sisterhood that transcends tribal, racial, and national bonds.",
    "They encourage good and forbid evil,": "Believers actively promote righteousness and discourage wrongdoing—the opposite of hypocrites. This isn't passive goodness but engaged community improvement. Every believer has responsibility to enjoin what Allah loves and prevent what He hates, according to their ability.",
    "establish prayer and pay alms-tax,": "They maintain the two pillars that connect them vertically to Allah (prayer) and horizontally to society (zakah). Regular prayer keeps their hearts attached to Allah; regular charity keeps their wealth purified and their community supported.",
    "and obey Allah and His Messenger.": "Their obedience is comprehensive—following both divine commands (Quran) and prophetic guidance (Sunnah). Unlike hypocrites who pick and choose, true believers submit completely to whatever Allah and His Messenger command.",
    "It is they who will be shown Allah's mercy.": "The promised outcome: Allah's mercy. All their efforts, struggles, and sacrifices will be met with divine mercy—forgiveness for their shortcomings, reward for their deeds, and protection from punishment.",
    "Surely Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah has complete power to fulfill His promise and perfect wisdom in rewarding His servants. His might means no one can prevent Him from blessing the believers; His wisdom means His reward system is perfectly just and generous."
  },
  72: {
    "Allah has promised the believers, both men and women, Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there forever,": "Allah's promise to believers is Paradise—not temporary visit but eternal residence. Rivers of water, milk, honey, and wine (unlike earthly wine) flow beneath gardens of unimaginable beauty. Forever—no end, no fear of expulsion, no worry about death.",
    "and splendid homes in the Gardens of Eternity,": "Beyond the gardens are beautiful dwellings (masakin tayyibah)—pleasant, pure, comfortable homes. Jannatu 'Adn (Gardens of Eternity/Eden) represents the permanent abode of bliss. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described palaces of gold and silver, with bricks of precious materials.",
    "and—above all—the pleasure of Allah.": "Here is the supreme reward: Allah's pleasure (ridwan). Greater than all the physical delights of Paradise is knowing that Allah is pleased with you. The Prophet (peace be upon him) narrated that Allah will say to the people of Paradise: 'I shall give you something better,' and when they ask what could be better than Paradise, He will say: 'My pleasure—I will never be angry with you again' (Bukhari and Muslim). This divine approval is the ultimate achievement.",
    "That is ˹truly˺ the ultimate triumph.": "Al-fawz al-'azim—the greatest victory, the supreme success. After all struggles, trials, and sacrifices of this world, the believer attains complete, eternal, perfect victory. Nothing compares to this triumph."
  },
  73: {
    "O Prophet! Struggle against the disbelievers and the hypocrites,": "The Prophet is commanded to engage in jihad against both open enemies (disbelievers) and hidden enemies (hypocrites). Against disbelievers, this could include military action when necessary. Against hypocrites, it primarily means ideological struggle—exposing their arguments, refuting their doubts, implementing justice, and not giving them positions of trust. Physical fighting against hypocrites was generally avoided because they claimed to be Muslim.",
    "and be firm with them.": "Being 'ghaleez' (firm, harsh, tough) doesn't mean cruelty but rather refusing to show weakness or make compromises on religious principles. The Prophet was gentle by nature, but with those who attacked Islam from within or without, firmness was required. This balance—mercy with believers, firmness with active enemies—is the prophetic way.",
    "Hell will be their home.": "The destination of both disbelievers and hypocrites is Hell. Whether they openly reject faith or secretly deny it, the end result is the same—Hellfire as their permanent residence.",
    "What an evil destination!": "A concluding statement of how terrible this outcome is. After all their scheming, plotting, and opposing the truth, they end up in the worst possible place. Their 'clever' strategies led them to the stupidest possible outcome."
  },
  74: {
    "They swear by Allah that they never said anything ˹blasphemous˺,": "When confronted about their mockery and blasphemous statements, hypocrites denied everything under oath. They used Allah's name to cover lies about insulting Him. This compounds their sin—false oaths added to blasphemy.",
    "while they did in fact utter a blasphemy,": "But they did say it. Allah knows what they said even if they deny it. Their private conversations, their whispered mockery, their treasonous discussions—all recorded.",
    "lost faith after accepting Islam,": "Whatever faith they claimed is now void. Their blasphemous words revealed their true disbelief. They apostated after appearing to be Muslim.",
    "and plotted what they could not carry out.": "They conspired against the Prophet (peace be upon him), possibly including assassination attempts. Some scholars mention a plot during the return from Tabuk where hypocrites planned to push the Prophet off a cliff, but Allah protected him. Their plots failed completely.",
    "It is only through resentment that they pay Allah and His Messenger back for enriching them out of His bounty!": "This exposes their twisted psychology. Allah and His Messenger actually improved their lives—Islam brought them from poverty to prosperity, from obscurity to significance, from tribal warfare to unified community. But instead of gratitude, they responded with resentment and opposition. They bit the hand that fed them. This ingratitude is especially ugly because it turns blessing into motivation for betrayal.",
    "If they repent, it will be better for them.": "Despite everything, the door of repentance remains open. If they genuinely return to Allah, acknowledge their wrongs, and change their ways, it will be better for them. Allah's mercy can cover even their enormous sins.",
    "But if they turn away, Allah will torment them with a painful punishment in this world and the Hereafter,": "If they persist in their hypocrisy, punishment awaits in both realms. In this world—exposure, disgrace, military defeat, loss of what they valued. In the Hereafter—eternal Hellfire.",
    "and they will have no one on earth to protect or help them.": "When Allah's punishment comes, no ally will save them, no helper will intervene. Their earthly connections, wealth, and schemes will all prove useless. They will be completely alone in facing divine justice."
  },
  75: {
    "And there are some who had made a vow to Allah:": "This verse refers to specific individuals who made solemn covenants with Allah. Some narrations mention Tha'labah ibn Hatib as an example—though scholars differ on the exact identification. Whoever they were, they made promises to Allah.",
    "\"If He gives us from His bounty, we will surely spend in charity and be of the righteous.\"": "Their vow was conditional: if Allah grants us wealth, we promise to be generous and righteous. They portrayed themselves as people who would do good if only they had the means. 'Just make us rich, and watch how charitable we'll be!' This is a promise many people make when they're poor—and often break when they become wealthy."
  },
  76: {
    "But when He gave them out of His bounty,": "Allah tested them by answering their prayer. He granted them the wealth they asked for, giving them the opportunity to fulfill their vow.",
    "they withheld it": "Instead of being generous as promised, they became miserly (bakhilu). They held onto their wealth tightly, refusing to share. The very wealth that was supposed to enable their charity became their excuse for stinginess.",
    "and turned away indifferently.": "They turned their backs on their promise to Allah and on the community that needed their support. 'Mu'ridun' indicates deliberate avoidance—they knew what they should do but consciously chose to ignore it. Their attitude was one of complete disregard for their sacred vow."
  },
  77: {
    "So He caused hypocrisy to plague their hearts until the Day they will meet Him,": "As a consequence of breaking their vow, Allah placed hypocrisy (nifaq) in their hearts—not temporarily but permanently, until they die and meet Allah. This is a terrifying punishment: their broken promise infected their hearts with a spiritual disease that became incurable. This teaches that breaking vows to Allah has profound spiritual consequences—it doesn't just remain as one sin but corrupts the entire heart.",
    "for breaking their promise to Allah": "The cause is explicitly stated: they broke their covenant with Allah. A promise to Allah is the most serious kind of promise. When they violated it, they essentially declared that Allah's covenant doesn't matter to them.",
    "and for their lies.": "They lied when making the vow—their intention was never sincere. Or they lied afterward, perhaps claiming they never made such promises or that they were fulfilling them. Either way, lying compounded their crime. Breaking a promise is betrayal; lying about it adds deception. Together, these sins transformed their hearts into vessels of permanent hypocrisy."
  },
  78: {
    "Do they not know that Allah ˹fully˺ knows their ˹evil˺ thoughts": "A rhetorical question challenging their foolishness. Did they think they could hide their stinginess, their broken vows, their true intentions from Allah? He knows their secret thoughts—the calculations of greed, the rationalizations for breaking promises, the hidden resentment.",
    "and secret talks,": "Even their private conversations with each other—discussing how to avoid giving charity, mocking the believers, planning their deceptions—all are known to Allah. Nothing whispered in the darkest room escapes His knowledge.",
    "and that Allah is the Knower of all unseen?": "Allah is 'Allam al-Ghuyub—the supreme knower of all hidden things. He knows what was, what is, what will be, and what would have been if things had been different. Against such complete knowledge, their attempts to hide their hypocrisy are utterly futile. This verse should instill both fear (Allah knows all my secret sins) and hope (Allah knows all my sincere efforts that no one else sees)."
  },
  79: {
    "˹There are˺ those who slander ˹some of˺ the believers for donating liberally": "The hypocrites criticized believers no matter what they did. When wealthy companions like Abdur-Rahman ibn Awf (may Allah be pleased with him) donated large amounts—he once gave half his wealth for the Tabuk expedition—they accused him of showing off, seeking reputation, or having ulterior motives. They couldn't accept that someone would genuinely give so much for Allah's sake.",
    "and mock others for giving only the little they can afford.": "When poor companions gave what little they could, the hypocrites mocked them too. Abu Aqeel al-Ansari (may Allah be pleased with him) worked all night irrigating date palms and earned two sa's (approximately 5-6 kg) of dates. He gave half to his family and half to charity. The hypocrites laughed: 'Allah doesn't need his handful of dates!' They belittled sincere efforts because they couldn't understand sacrifice for Allah. Whether you give much or little, hypocrites find fault—revealing that their problem is not with the amount but with faith itself.",
    "Allah will throw their mockery back at them,": "Divine justice operates through perfect reciprocity. They mocked believers, so Allah mocks them. Their ridicule returns to them—their end will be something truly worthy of mockery. In the Hereafter, when they face punishment while believers enter Paradise, who will be laughing then? This 'mocking back' is a form of divine irony where their arrogance becomes their humiliation.",
    "and they will suffer a painful punishment.": "Beyond mockery, they face actual torment. Mocking sincere charity is a serious sin because it discourages good deeds and shows contempt for faith. Their punishment matches their crime—they caused pain to believers through ridicule, so they receive painful punishment in return."
  },
  80: {
    "˹It does not matter˺ whether you ˹O Prophet˺ pray for them to be forgiven or not.": "This addresses the Prophet's (peace be upon him) natural inclination toward mercy. Out of his compassionate nature, he might want to seek forgiveness for even these hypocrites. But Allah informs him that his prayers would make no difference for those who have sealed their hearts against faith.",
    "Even if you pray for their forgiveness seventy times, Allah will never forgive them.": "The number seventy in Arabic often indicates a very large number. Even if the Prophet prayed countless times for these people, Allah would not forgive them. This isn't because the Prophet's prayers lack value—quite the opposite, his prayers are immensely valuable. But these individuals have disqualified themselves from receiving forgiveness. When the chief hypocrite Abdullah ibn Ubayy died, his son (a sincere Muslim) asked the Prophet to pray for him. The Prophet did, out of kindness, but this verse clarified the futility of such prayers for confirmed hypocrites.",
    "That is because they have lost faith in Allah and His Messenger.": "The reason for their unforgiveability: they rejected Allah and His Messenger. Forgiveness requires some basis of faith; these people have none. Their persistent, knowing rejection of truth—while having full access to it—puts them beyond the reach of mercy they consciously refuse.",
    "And Allah does not guide the rebellious people.": "Guidance requires receptivity. These fasiqun (rebellious transgressors) have closed their hearts so completely that divine guidance cannot enter. It's not that Allah is unable to guide them but that they have made themselves unguided through their stubborn rebellion. Allah does not force guidance upon those who determinedly reject it."
  },
  81: {
    "Those ˹hypocrites˺ who remained behind rejoiced for doing so in defiance of the Messenger of Allah": "The Tabuk expedition took place during an extremely hot summer when dates were ripe and shade was precious. Hypocrites who stayed behind were happy about their decision—not ashamed or regretful, but pleased. Their happiness was specifically 'in defiance' of the Prophet—they were glad to have disobeyed, relieved to have avoided hardship, proud of their cleverness in escaping the difficult march.",
    "and hated ˹the prospect of˺ striving with their wealth and their lives in the cause of Allah.": "They despised the idea of sacrificing comfort, money, or safety for Islam. Jihad requires giving up what one loves—wealth for expenses and equipment, physical comfort for hardship, safety for risk. The hypocrites loved their possessions and lives too much to sacrifice them for anything, let alone for a faith they didn't truly hold.",
    "They said ˹to one another˺, \"Do not march forth in the heat.\"": "They justified their cowardice with the excuse of hot weather. 'It's too hot to travel! We'll die from heat exhaustion!' They discouraged each other and possibly sincere believers too. This excuse sounds reasonable on the surface—the Arabian summer is brutally hot—but it prioritizes physical comfort over spiritual duty.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"The Fire of Hell is far hotter!\"": "Allah commands the Prophet to deliver a devastating response. You're worried about this summer heat? Hell's fire is infinitely hotter. You avoid temporary discomfort by earning eternal burning. The comparison is meant to shock them into perspective—a few weeks of hot marching versus endless inferno.",
    "If only they could comprehend!": "They lack understanding (fiqh)—deep comprehension of reality. If they truly understood what awaits them, they would gladly endure any earthly heat to escape the Hereafter's fire. Their short-sighted thinking trades eternal torment for temporary comfort."
  },
  82: {
    "So let them laugh a little—": "Let them enjoy their momentary relief, their smug satisfaction at avoiding difficulty. Let them chuckle at the believers who marched in the heat while they stayed comfortable. This laughter is 'qalil' (little)—brief, limited, fleeting. Worldly pleasures, even for a full lifetime, are short compared to eternity.",
    "they will weep much": "Their weeping will be 'kathir' (much)—abundant, prolonged, unending. In Hell, they will cry rivers of tears that eventually burn their faces. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described Hell's inhabitants weeping until they have no more tears, then weeping blood. Their brief laughter is followed by endless crying.",
    "as a reward for what they have committed.": "Their weeping is payment, recompense for their deeds. They earned this outcome through their choices—staying behind, discouraging others, mocking believers, preferring comfort over obedience. Justice demands that their momentary pleasure be balanced with extended pain. The contrast between 'little' and 'much' captures the foolishness of their trade."
  },
  83: {
    "If Allah returns you ˹O Prophet˺ to a group of them": "When the Prophet (peace be upon him) returns from Tabuk to Medina, he will encounter those who stayed behind. Allah anticipates their behavior and prepares the Prophet's response.",
    "and they ask to go forth with you,": "Hypocrites might ask to join future expeditions—either to maintain their cover, to share in potential war booty, or because social pressure makes staying behind embarrassing. They might approach the Prophet seeking permission to accompany the next campaign.",
    "say, \"You will not ever go forth or fight an enemy along with me.": "The Prophet is commanded to reject them permanently. The word 'abadan' (ever) indicates a lasting prohibition. They lost their chance. They are banned from participating in military campaigns with the Prophet because their presence would be harmful rather than helpful—they would spread discord, flee at critical moments, and weaken morale.",
    "You preferred to stay behind the first time, so stay with those ˹helpless˺ who remain behind.\"": "Their punishment fits their crime. They chose to stay behind when it mattered, so now staying behind becomes their permanent status. They must remain with the 'khalifin'—those legitimately excused like women, children, elderly, and sick. For men who prided themselves on their courage and independence, being grouped with the helpless was deeply humiliating. Their choice became their sentence."
  },
  84: {
    "And do not ever offer ˹funeral˺ prayers for any of their dead,": "The Prophet is prohibited from praying the janazah (funeral prayer) for confirmed hypocrites. This was revealed after the Prophet prayed for Abdullah ibn Ubayy, the chief hypocrite, at his son's request. After this verse, such prayers were forbidden. The funeral prayer is an intercession for the deceased, asking Allah's mercy—it's inappropriate for those who rejected Allah's mercy while alive.",
    "nor stand by their grave ˹at burial˺,": "Beyond the prayer, even standing at their graves to make du'a or show respect is prohibited. Graves of believers are visited for prayer and remembrance; the graves of hypocrites deserve no such honor. This complete dissociation in death matches their dissociation from true faith in life.",
    "for they have lost faith in Allah and His Messenger": "The reason is their fundamental disbelief. Whatever they claimed publicly, they rejected Allah and His Messenger internally. Their deaths without repentance sealed their fate.",
    "and died rebellious.": "They died in a state of fisq (rebellion, transgression). Their final condition was one of defiance against Allah. Since they died without faith, treating them as believers in death would be dishonest and inappropriate. Islamic funeral rites are for Muslims; those who die rejecting Islam are excluded."
  },
  85: {
    "And let neither their wealth nor children impress you ˹O Prophet˺.": "This repeats an earlier theme (verse 55), emphasizing its importance. The hypocrites might appear blessed with worldly success—prosperous businesses, many children, comfortable lives. Such appearances can be deceptive, making people think Allah favors them.",
    "Allah only intends to torment them through these things in this world,": "Their apparent blessings are actually punishments. Their wealth brings worry, greed, and distraction from what matters. Their children may cause them grief or lead them to compromise their principles. What looks like blessing is actually a test they're failing and a source of ongoing spiritual pain.",
    "and ˹then˺ their souls will depart while they are disbelievers.": "The worst part: they die in disbelief. All their wealth stays behind; only their empty souls proceed to judgment. They spent their lives accumulating what couldn't save them and neglecting what could. The phrase emphasizes the horror of dying without faith—the moment when truth becomes clear but too late to change."
  },
  86: {
    "Whenever a sûrah is revealed stating, \"Believe in Allah and struggle along with His Messenger,\"": "When Quranic verses came commanding faith and jihad, calling believers to action and sacrifice, this put pressure on everyone to respond. The revelation demanded a response—would people obey or make excuses?",
    "the rich among them would ask to be exempt,": "It was specifically the wealthy (ulu al-tawl—those with resources and capability) who sought exemption. This is ironic: those most able to contribute were most eager to avoid contributing. Their wealth should have made sacrifice easier, but their attachment to it made them reluctant. The poor often gave more willingly than the rich because they had less to lose and more faith to gain.",
    "saying, \"Leave us with those who remain behind.\"": "They asked to be grouped with the legitimately excused—the old, sick, disabled, and women. Men of means and ability wanted to be classified with the helpless. This reveals both cowardice and shamelessness. They weren't embarrassed to avoid duty; they openly requested exemption. Their wealth protected them from social pressure that would shame poorer people into participating."
  },
  87: {
    "They preferred to stay behind with the helpless,": "They were content—even pleased—to be among the 'khawalif' (those who remain behind, often referring to women and children staying home). For Arab men who valued honor and bravery, this should have been humiliating. But they had so lost their sense of honor that remaining with the helpless didn't bother them. Comfort mattered more than dignity.",
    "and their hearts have been sealed so they do not comprehend.": "Allah sealed their hearts as a consequence of their choices. They chose worldly comfort over divine duty so many times that their hearts became incapable of understanding spiritual realities. They can no longer comprehend (yafqahun) the truth, the value of sacrifice, or the danger they're in. This spiritual blindness is both their punishment and the reason for their continued failure."
  },
  88: {
    "But the Messenger and the believers with him strived with their wealth and their lives.": "In contrast to the hypocrites, the Prophet (peace be upon him) and sincere believers sacrificed everything. They gave their money to fund the expedition, their bodies to endure the march, their lives risking death. The contrast is stark: hypocrites hoarded and hid; believers gave and went forward.",
    "They will have all the best,": "The 'khayrat' (all good things, the best) belong to these believers. Every blessing in this world and the next is for them. While hypocrites cling to temporary possessions, believers earn eternal rewards. The truly good things—Allah's pleasure, Paradise, honor in both worlds—belong to those who sacrifice.",
    "and it is they who will be successful.": "They are the 'muflihun'—the successful, the prosperous, the winners. Success is redefined: not measured by wealth preserved but by reward earned, not by comfort enjoyed but by purpose fulfilled. True success is achieving Allah's pleasure, and that belongs only to those who strive."
  },
  89: {
    "Allah has prepared for them Gardens under which rivers flow,": "Paradise awaits these strivers—gardens of unimaginable beauty with rivers flowing beneath. 'A'adda' (prepared) indicates it's already waiting for them, ready for their arrival. Allah has personally prepared their reward, making it perfect and complete.",
    "to stay there forever.": "Khalideen fiha—eternal residence. Unlike worldly homes that decay, are sold, or must be left at death, Paradise is permanent. No lease expires, no mortgage threatens, no death forces departure. Forever in perfect bliss.",
    "That is the ultimate triumph.": "Al-fawz al-'azim—the supreme victory, the greatest success. After all worldly struggles end, this is the outcome that matters. Those who sacrificed comfort for obedience, wealth for duty, and safety for faith achieve the only victory worth having."
  },
  90: {
    "Some nomadic Arabs ˹also˺ came with excuses, seeking exemption.": "Not only the hypocrites in Medina but also Bedouin Arabs from surrounding areas brought excuses. They came specifically to the Prophet seeking permission to stay behind. 'Mu'adhdhirun' could mean those with excuses or those making false excuses—scholars differ, but the context suggests these were often insincere.",
    "And those who were untrue to Allah and His Messenger remained behind ˹with no excuse˺.": "Even worse than those with excuses were those who simply didn't show up at all. They didn't even bother coming to the Prophet with justifications—they just stayed away. Their lies to Allah and His Messenger (claiming faith while having none) were demonstrated through their complete absence.",
    "The unfaithful among them will be afflicted with a painful punishment.": "Those who disbelieved among these nomads will face severe punishment. Not all Bedouins were hypocrites—some were sincere. But those who had kufr in their hearts while claiming Islam will suffer painfully. Their desert distance from Medina didn't protect them from Allah's knowledge or judgment."
  },
  91: {
    "There is no blame on the weak,": "Those who are physically weak—whether from old age, disability, or constitutional frailty—are excused from military jihad. Islam doesn't demand the impossible. A person who genuinely cannot make the journey or fight is not sinful for staying behind.",
    "the sick,": "Those suffering from illness that would prevent them from participating or would worsen with the journey are excused. Health limitations are recognized as valid reasons for exemption.",
    "or those lacking the means ˹if they stay behind˺,": "Poverty is also a valid excuse. Those who cannot afford equipment, provisions, or transportation are not required to go. Islam doesn't burden people beyond their capacity. Many poor companions desperately wanted to join but couldn't afford it.",
    "as long as they are true to Allah and His Messenger.": "The condition is sincerity. These exemptions apply only to those who genuinely believe and would participate if they could. They should still support the cause in whatever way possible—through prayers, encouragement, or any assistance within their means. Their hearts should be with the army even if their bodies cannot be.",
    "There is no blame on the good-doers.": "Those who do good according to their ability (muhsinun) are not subject to criticism. They're doing their best within their constraints. Allah judges by intention and capacity, not by uniform standards ignoring individual circumstances.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah forgives and shows mercy. Even if legitimately excused people feel guilt about not participating, Allah understands and forgives. His mercy encompasses those who wanted to serve but couldn't."
  },
  92: {
    "Nor ˹is there any blame on˺ those who came to you ˹O Prophet˺ for mounts,": "This verse describes a specific group known as 'al-bakka'un' (the weepers). These companions came to the Prophet asking for animals to ride so they could join the expedition. They were too poor to provide their own transportation.",
    "then when you said, \"I can find no mounts for you,\"": "The Prophet had to tell them that resources were limited and he couldn't provide them with mounts. All available animals were already allocated. This was genuinely heartbreaking for these eager believers.",
    "they left with eyes overflowing with tears": "Their response reveals their sincerity—they wept. Their tears weren't from self-pity but from grief at missing the opportunity to serve Allah. They cried because they couldn't participate in jihad with the Prophet. Scholars mention companions like Abu Layla al-Mazini and others who wept so much their tears 'overflowed.'",
    "out of grief that they had nothing to contribute.": "Their sorrow was specifically because they lacked means to contribute. They wanted desperately to give—their bodies, their effort, anything—but poverty prevented them. Compare this to the wealthy hypocrites who had everything and gave nothing. These poor men had nothing yet wanted to give everything. Their tears were more valuable to Allah than the hypocrites' wealth."
  },
  93: {
    "Blame is only on those who seek exemption from you although they have the means.": "The genuine wrongdoers are identified: those who have wealth and capability but still ask to be excused. They have no valid reason—no weakness, no sickness, no poverty. Their only motivation is unwillingness to sacrifice comfort and wealth. On such people, blame (sabil—a way of holding accountable) is justified.",
    "They preferred to stay behind with the helpless,": "Like the others, they chose to remain with those legitimately excused. But for them, this was shameful—they had no excuse to be in that category. They voluntarily joined the ranks of the unable despite being fully able.",
    "and Allah has sealed their hearts so they do not realize ˹the consequences˺.": "Divine sealing of their hearts means they cannot understand (ya'lamun) the gravity of their situation. They don't perceive the danger they're in, the punishment awaiting them, or the opportunity they're wasting. Their spiritual blindness is both cause and consequence of their choices."
  },
  94: {
    "They will make excuses to you ˹believers˺ when you return to them.": "Allah predicts their behavior: when the army returns to Medina, those who stayed behind will come with elaborate excuses. They'll explain why they couldn't possibly have joined, citing various justifications, hoping to avoid blame.",
    "Say, \"Make no excuses, ˹for˺ we will not believe you.": "The Prophet and believers are commanded to reject their excuses outright. Don't waste time listening to their lies—they won't be believed anyway. Their track record has destroyed their credibility.",
    "Allah has already informed us about your ˹true˺ state ˹of faith˺.": "Divine revelation has exposed their reality. The Quran has told believers exactly who these people are and what they're really like. There's no point in hearing their version—Allah's version is already known.",
    "Your ˹future˺ deeds will be observed by Allah and His Messenger as well.": "Moving forward, their actions will be watched. They might fool people temporarily with words, but their deeds will reveal their truth. Allah sees everything, and the Prophet will observe their behavior over time.",
    "And you will be returned to the Knower of the seen and unseen, then He will inform you of what you used to do.\"": "Ultimately, everyone returns to Allah who knows both what's public and what's hidden. On that Day, He will inform them of everything they did—every excuse, every lie, every moment of hidden disbelief. Nothing will be forgotten or overlooked."
  },
  95: {
    "When you return, they will swear to you by Allah so that you may leave them alone.": "They'll take oaths by Allah trying to make believers drop the matter and stop criticizing them. They want to avoid social consequences, so they'll use Allah's name to close the conversation. 'We swear by Allah we had valid reasons—just leave us alone!'",
    "So leave them alone—": "Allah commands: fine, leave them alone—but not in the way they want. Don't engage with them, don't argue with them, don't waste energy on them. Ignore them completely.",
    "they are truly evil.": "They are 'rijs'—filth, impurity, evil. This is a strong condemnation. Their inner corruption makes them spiritually contaminated. Believers shouldn't seek their company or approval.",
    "Hell will be their home as a reward for what they have committed.": "Their final dwelling is Hell—'ma'wa' implies a place of refuge and dwelling, used ironically here. The place they'll end up is not the comfortable home they protected by staying behind but the eternal fire of Hell. This is their earned 'reward' for what they accumulated of sins and hypocrisy."
  },
  96: {
    "They will swear to you in order to please you.": "Their goal is human approval. They want believers to accept them, to forgive and forget, to restore normal relations. Their oaths are designed to achieve social reconciliation.",
    "And even if you are pleased with them,": "Even if their efforts succeed and the believers are satisfied with their explanations—accepting their oaths and treating them normally again—",
    "Allah will never be pleased with the rebellious people.": "Allah's pleasure is separate from human pleasure. Believers might be fooled, but Allah is not. His displeasure with the fasiqun (rebellious) remains regardless of whether humans forgive them. This is crucial: human forgiveness doesn't equal divine forgiveness. They need to make things right with Allah, not just with people. And Allah will never be pleased with those who persist in rebellion without genuine repentance."
  },
  97: {
    "The nomadic Arabs ˹around Medina˺ are far worse in disbelief and hypocrisy,": "The Bedouin Arabs—desert nomads living far from urban centers—are characterized as having more severe disbelief and hypocrisy than others. This isn't a blanket condemnation of all Bedouins but describes a tendency: their isolation made them more prone to ignorance and harder in their hearts. Their harsh desert life and distance from the Prophet's teachings affected their receptivity.",
    "and less likely to know the laws revealed by Allah to His Messenger.": "They had less access to religious knowledge. Without regular attendance at the Prophet's mosque, without hearing Friday sermons, without daily interaction with knowledgeable companions, they remained ignorant of Islamic law's details. The 'hudud' (limits, laws) of revelation were unknown to them. This explains—though doesn't excuse—their behavior.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "Allah knows who among them is genuinely ignorant versus willfully rebellious. He judges with wisdom, accounting for circumstances. This phrase reminds us that not all Bedouins were the same—Allah distinguishes between individuals based on perfect knowledge."
  },
  98: {
    "And among the nomads are those who consider what they donate to be a loss": "Some Bedouins viewed mandatory zakah and voluntary charity as 'maghram'—a fine, penalty, or forced loss. Instead of seeing charity as investment in the Hereafter or purification of wealth, they saw it as money taken from them against their will. This attitude reveals their lack of faith in divine reward.",
    "and await your misfortune.": "They secretly hope for Muslims to fail—for military defeat, economic collapse, or the Prophet's death. They're waiting for 'dawair' (turns of fortune, calamities) to befall believers so they can stop pretending to be Muslim and stop paying what they consider extortion.",
    "May ill-fortune befall them!": "Allah turns their wish back on them: the misfortune they desire for others will befall them instead. 'Da'iratu al-saw' (the circle of evil) will encompass them. What goes around comes around—their evil wishes return to their own heads.",
    "And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears their secret wishes and whispered hopes for Muslim failure. He knows what's in their hearts. No ill-wish escapes His hearing; no hidden hostility escapes His knowledge."
  },
  99: {
    "However, among the nomadic Arabs are those who believe in Allah and the Last Day,": "Not all Bedouins were hypocrites—this crucial clarification prevents unfair generalization. Some genuinely believed in Allah and the Hereafter. Their distance from Medina didn't prevent sincere faith. Among the desert-dwellers were righteous souls.",
    "and consider what they donate as a means of coming closer to Allah": "These believing Bedouins viewed charity completely differently. For them, donations were 'qurubat'—means of drawing near to Allah. Each dirham spent for His sake brought them closer to Him. They understood charity as spiritual investment, not financial loss.",
    "and ˹receiving˺ the prayers of the Messenger.": "They also hoped their charity would earn the Prophet's prayers for them. When he received charity and made du'a for the giver, they valued this immensely. The Prophet (peace be upon him) would often pray for those who contributed to good causes, and these believers sought that blessing.",
    "It will certainly bring them closer.": "Allah confirms: yes, it is indeed qurbah (closeness) for them. Their understanding is correct; their hope is not misplaced. Their charity truly does bring them nearer to Allah and earns the Prophet's prayers.",
    "Allah will admit them into His mercy.": "Their sincere faith and charitable spirit qualify them for Allah's mercy. They will be entered into it—enveloped, surrounded, and blessed by divine mercy in this world and the next.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "For these sincere believers, Allah's nature as Forgiving and Merciful works in their favor. Their minor faults are forgiven; their good deeds are multiplied. The same divine attributes that spell doom for hypocrites spell salvation for the faithful."
  },
  100: {
    "As for the foremost—the first of the Emigrants": "The 'Sabiqun' (foremost) are given the highest rank. The Muhajirin (Emigrants) were those who left Mecca, abandoning their homes, wealth, and families to preserve their faith. The 'first' among them were those who emigrated early—before the conquest of Mecca—when emigration meant the greatest sacrifice and danger. They include luminaries like Abu Bakr, Umar, Uthman, Ali, and others who embraced Islam early and sacrificed everything (may Allah be pleased with them all).",
    "and the Helpers": "The Ansar (Helpers) were the Muslims of Medina—primarily from the Aws and Khazraj tribes—who welcomed the emigrants, shared their homes and wealth, and supported the Prophet (peace be upon him). They gave half of everything they owned to their emigrant brothers. Their generosity was unprecedented. The 'first' among them were those who embraced Islam before the Prophet's arrival and pledged allegiance at Aqabah.",
    "—and those who follow them in goodness,": "This extends the blessing to all subsequent generations who follow the path of these pioneers 'in goodness' (bi-ihsan). Anyone who emulates their faith, sacrifice, and righteousness shares in this divine approval. This includes Muslims throughout history and until the Day of Judgment who follow the companions' example sincerely.",
    "Allah is pleased with them and they are pleased with Him.": "This is the ultimate achievement: mutual pleasure between Creator and creation. Allah is pleased with their faith, sacrifices, and struggles. They are pleased with Allah's guidance, support, and rewards. This divine pleasure is greater than any other blessing. The Prophet (peace be upon him) narrated that Allah will tell Paradise's inhabitants: 'My pleasure upon you—I will never be angry with you again.'",
    "And He has prepared for them Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there for ever and ever.": "Their reward is Paradise—prepared and waiting. Rivers flow beneath its gardens; their residence is eternal (khalideen fiha abadan—the double emphasis on forever indicates absolute permanence). The preparation implies personalized, perfect reward already designed for them.",
    "That is the ultimate triumph.": "Al-fawz al-'azim—the greatest victory achievable. After all trials of this short life, they attain infinite, eternal success. Nothing compares to this triumph."
  },
  101: {
    "Some of the nomads around you ˹believers˺ are hypocrites,": "Hypocrisy wasn't limited to Medina's residents. Some Bedouin Arabs surrounding the city were also hypocrites, maintaining the appearance of Islam while harboring disbelief. Their distance from the Prophet's mosque didn't protect them from spiritual corruption.",
    "as are some of the people of Medina.": "Even within Medina itself—the city of the Prophet, the center of Islamic learning—hypocrites existed. Proximity to guidance doesn't guarantee acceptance of it. Living near the Prophet didn't automatically make one sincere.",
    "They have mastered hypocrisy.": "'Maradu 'ala al-nifaq' means they became experts, veterans, specialists in hypocrisy. They practiced it so long that they perfected it. Their deception was so polished that it became undetectable to ordinary observation. They knew exactly how to appear Muslim while being disbelievers inside.",
    "They are not known to you ˹O Prophet˺;": "Even the Prophet (peace be upon him), despite his insight, didn't know all of them. Allah revealed some hypocrites' identities to him, but others remained hidden. This shows that detecting such sophisticated hypocrisy is beyond human capacity. It's also a protection for the Prophet—he judged by appearances as required, leaving hidden matters to Allah.",
    "they are known to Us.": "But Allah knows them completely. Every hidden thought, every whispered conversation, every fake prayer—all recorded and known. No hypocrisy, however masterful, escapes divine knowledge.",
    "We will punish them twice ˹in this world˺,": "They will face double punishment in this life. Scholars interpret this variously: exposure and disgrace, plus punishment at death; or worldly calamities plus torment in the grave; or being compelled to pay zakah which pains them, plus punishment at death. Whatever the specifics, their worldly existence includes multiple forms of suffering.",
    "then they will be brought back ˹to their Lord˺ for a tremendous punishment.": "After the worldly punishments comes the Hereafter's tremendous torment. 'Azim' (tremendous) indicates unimaginable severity. The hypocrites occupy the lowest depths of Hell, as stated elsewhere in the Quran (4:145). Their sophisticated deception earns them the most severe destination."
  },
  102: {
    "Some others have confessed their wrongdoing:": "This refers to a different group—believers who stayed behind from Tabuk without valid excuse but later repented. Unlike hypocrites who made excuses, these individuals admitted their fault. Abu Lubabah and others tied themselves to pillars in the Prophet's mosque, refusing to release themselves until Allah accepted their repentance. Confession is the first step to forgiveness.",
    "they have mixed goodness with evil.": "Their record contains both good and bad. They had genuine faith and previous good deeds (salih) but also committed this sin (sayyi') of staying behind. They weren't pure hypocrites—they had real faith. But they weren't perfect believers either—they had failed this test. Most Muslims fall into this category: imperfect believers with mixed records.",
    "It is right to hope that Allah will turn to them in mercy.": "'Asa' (perhaps, it is hoped) from Allah indicates near-certainty—when Allah uses this expression, it means He will do it. Their hope for forgiveness is well-founded. Allah turning to them (tawbah) means He accepts their repentance and restores His favor.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah's nature supports their hope. He is Ghafur (perpetually forgiving) and Rahim (especially merciful). His forgiveness is not reluctant but flows from His essential nature. For those who sincerely confess and repent, divine mercy is abundant."
  },
  103: {
    "Take from their wealth ˹O Prophet˺ charity to purify and bless them,": "The Prophet is commanded to accept charity from these repentant believers. This charity serves two purposes: 'tutahhiruhum' (purifies them) from the spiritual stain of their sin, and 'tuzakkihim' (blesses them, makes them grow) spiritually. Charity given in repentance cleanses the soul and elevates the giver. This also shows that repentance may include practical acts, not just verbal confession.",
    "and pray for them—": "The Prophet should make du'a for them, asking Allah to forgive and bless them. When he accepted their charity, he would pray: 'O Allah, bless the family of so-and-so.' This prophetic prayer carried special weight and blessing.",
    "surely your prayer is a source of comfort for them.": "The Prophet's du'a brings 'sakan'—peace, tranquility, comfort—to their hearts. After the anxiety of sin and uncertainty of forgiveness, the Prophet's prayer reassures them that they're accepted back. His prayer confirms their restoration to the community and Allah's pleasure.",
    "And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears the Prophet's prayers and knows the sincerity of these repentant hearts. Both the prayer and the repentance are fully known to Him, and He responds accordingly."
  },
  104: {
    "Do they not know that Allah alone accepts the repentance of His servants": "A rhetorical question emphasizing what should be obvious: Allah Himself directly accepts repentance. No intermediary is needed; no one else has this power. When a servant turns back to Allah sincerely, Allah directly receives that repentance. The word 'huwa' (He alone) emphasizes exclusivity.",
    "and receives ˹their˺ charity,": "Similarly, Allah Himself receives charity. Though the Prophet physically takes the donation, spiritually Allah is the one accepting it. Every sincere charity reaches Allah. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Charity falls into Allah's Hand before it falls into the beggar's hand' (Tirmidhi). This elevates the act of giving from mere social transaction to divine worship.",
    "and that Allah alone is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful?": "Two divine names conclude the verse: Al-Tawwab (the One who constantly accepts repentance, who turns frequently toward His servants) and Al-Rahim (the especially Merciful). These names should inspire confidence in the repentant—Allah's very nature is to accept those who return to Him and to show them mercy."
  },
  105: {
    "Tell ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Do as you will.": "This statement is both invitation and warning. For the repentant, it encourages continued good deeds. For others, it's a warning: do whatever you choose, but know that everything is observed. Free will comes with accountability.",
    "Your deeds will be observed by Allah, His Messenger, and the believers.": "Triple observation: Allah sees everything including intentions; the Prophet witnesses his community's condition; believers observe each other's outward actions. Nothing is truly private. This awareness should motivate good deeds and discourage sins.",
    "And you will be returned to the Knower of the seen and unseen,": "Ultimately everyone returns to Allah who knows 'al-ghayb' (the hidden, unseen) and 'al-shahadah' (the witnessed, apparent). He knows what people showed and what they hid, what they did publicly and privately, what they said and what they thought.",
    "then He will inform you of what you used to do.\"": "On that Day, Allah will inform each person of their complete record. Nothing forgotten, nothing overlooked. Every deed, word, and intention presented. This is both warning for sinners and encouragement for the righteous—all good deeds, even forgotten ones, will be shown and rewarded."
  },
  106: {
    "And some others are left for Allah's decision,": "A third category exists: 'murjawna li-amrillah'—those whose case is deferred, awaiting Allah's command. These were three companions—Ka'b ibn Malik, Murarah ibn al-Rabi', and Hilal ibn Umayyah (may Allah be pleased with them)—who stayed behind from Tabuk without excuse and truthfully confessed but whose forgiveness was delayed. For fifty days, the Prophet and all Muslims were commanded not to speak to them.",
    "either to punish them or turn to them in mercy.": "Their fate remained uncertain during this period. Would Allah punish them or forgive them? They didn't know, and this uncertainty itself was part of their trial. They lived in anguish, isolated from the community, waiting for divine verdict.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "Allah knew their hearts—their genuine faith and sincere repentance—and His wisdom dictated this period of waiting. The delay wasn't arbitrary but served to purify them further and demonstrate the seriousness of abandoning the Prophet's call. Their eventual forgiveness (verse 118) would come after this severe test."
  },
  107: {
    "There are also those ˹hypocrites˺ who set up a mosque ˹only˺ to cause harm,": "Some hypocrites built a mosque near Quba with evil intentions. They called it a mosque, but it was 'Masjid Dirar' (Mosque of Harm). Their first purpose: 'diraran'—to harm the Muslim community, specifically to draw people away from the established Quba Mosque.",
    "promote disbelief,": "'Kufran'—to spread disbelief disguised as worship. The building looked like a mosque but would serve as a center for undermining Islam. Hypocrites would gather there to plot against believers under the cover of religious activity.",
    "divide the believers,": "'Tafreeqan bayn al-mu'mineen'—to split the unified Muslim community. By creating a competing mosque, they hoped to create factions, jealousy, and division. Unity was the Muslims' strength; division was the hypocrites' goal.",
    "and as a base for those who had previously fought against Allah and His Messenger.": "'Irsadan'—a watchtower, an outpost, a base for Abu 'Amir al-Rahib (the monk), a man who had fought against the Prophet and fled to the Romans. The hypocrites built this mosque to await his return with a Roman army. It would serve as his headquarters.",
    "They will definitely swear, \"We intended nothing but good,\"": "When questioned, they would take oaths claiming pure intentions: 'We just wanted to provide a closer mosque for elderly and sick people, especially during rainy nights!' Their excuse sounded reasonable, even compassionate.",
    "but Allah bears witness that they are surely liars.": "Allah testifies against them—their claims are lies. Their real motives were the four mentioned above: harm, disbelief, division, and hosting enemies. No oath could override divine testimony."
  },
  108: {
    "Do not ˹O Prophet˺ ever pray in it.": "The Prophet is prohibited from praying in Masjid Dirar—ever ('abadan'). This nullifies its status as a valid mosque. Upon returning from Tabuk, the Prophet sent companions to demolish and burn it. A building erected for evil purposes cannot be sanctified by prophetic prayer.",
    "Certainly, a mosque founded on righteousness from the first day is more worthy of your prayers.": "Quba Mosque, built when the Prophet first arrived in Medina, was founded on taqwa (righteousness, God-consciousness) from its first day. Its foundation was sincere faith; its purpose was genuine worship. Such a mosque deserves the Prophet's prayers. The contrast is stark: one mosque built on taqwa, another on harm.",
    "In it are men who love to be purified.": "The people of Quba Mosque love 'tatahur'—spiritual and physical purification. They care about cleansing their hearts from sins and their bodies for worship. The Prophet asked them about this and learned they used water after using the bathroom—a practice he praised.",
    "And Allah loves those who purify themselves.": "Divine love is earned through purification. Those who strive for purity in worship, body, and soul earn Allah's love. This is the community the Prophet should support—not hypocrites hiding behind mosque walls, but sincere believers striving for purity."
  },
  109: {
    "Which is better: those who laid the foundation of their building on the fear and pleasure of Allah,": "Allah presents a powerful comparison. One group builds on taqwa (consciousness of Allah) and seeking His ridwan (pleasure). Their foundation is solid, permanent, blessed—invisible but unshakeable.",
    "or those who did so on the edge of a crumbling cliff that tumbled down with them into the Fire of Hell?": "The other group builds on 'shafa jurufin haar'—the edge of a hollow, undermined, collapsing cliff. The image is vivid: beautiful structure built on unstable ground that will inevitably collapse. And when it collapses, it takes them into Hellfire. External appearances meant nothing; the foundation was rotten.",
    "And Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people.": "These wrongdoers (zalimun) are denied divine guidance. Their injustice—using religious forms for evil purposes—disqualifies them from Allah's help. They built to harm; they will be harmed. They built to deceive; they will be exposed."
  },
  110: {
    "The building which they erected will never cease to fuel hypocrisy in their hearts": "Even after the mosque was destroyed, its effect persists in their hearts. The 'bunya' (structure) they built continues generating 'raybah' (doubt, suspicion, hypocrisy) within them. Their evil project didn't just fail externally; it corrupted them internally.",
    "until their hearts are torn apart.": "'Taqatta'a qulubuhum'—until their hearts are cut to pieces. This could mean: until they die (hearts stop functioning); until they repent (hearts change completely); or until the Day of Judgment (hearts are examined). The continuous hypocrisy only ends through such drastic transformation.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "Allah knows their hearts' condition and wisely allows this consequence. Their evil intention backfired—instead of harming others, it poisoned themselves. Divine wisdom ensures that plotting against Islam ultimately harms only the plotters."
  },
  111: {
    "Allah has indeed purchased from the believers their lives and wealth in exchange for Paradise.": "This verse describes the most extraordinary transaction in existence. Allah—who already owns everything—'purchases' believers' lives and wealth. The price: Paradise. The seller: believers. The buyer: Allah Himself. This commercial metaphor elevates sacrifice for Allah's cause to a business deal with the Creator—one that the believer cannot lose.",
    "They fight in the cause of Allah and kill or are killed.": "The transaction is fulfilled through jihad. Believers fight for Allah's cause—they either defeat the enemy (yaqtulun—they kill) or achieve martyrdom (yuqtalun—they are killed). Either outcome fulfills the contract. Victory in this world or Paradise in the next—both are winning.",
    "This is a true promise binding on Him in the Torah, the Gospel, and the Quran.": "This promise isn't new to Islam; it was made in all divine scriptures. The Torah, the Gospel, and the Quran all record Allah's promise to reward those who sacrifice for His cause. This continuity demonstrates the unchanging nature of divine truth across revelations.",
    "And whose promise is truer than Allah's?": "A rhetorical question with an obvious answer: no one's promise is more reliable than Allah's. Humans break promises; Allah never does. Contracts fail; divine covenants are guaranteed. If Allah promises Paradise for sacrifice, that promise is certain.",
    "So rejoice in the exchange you have made with Him.": "'Fastabshiru'—rejoice, celebrate, be overjoyed! You've made the best deal possible. You've traded temporary life for eternal life, limited wealth for unlimited reward, passing world for permanent Paradise. What better bargain could exist?",
    "That is ˹truly˺ the ultimate triumph.": "Al-fawz al-'azim again—the supreme victory. Selling to Allah and receiving Paradise is the greatest success any human can achieve."
  },
  112: {
    "˹It is the believers˺ who repent,": "Al-ta'ibun—those who constantly repent, turning back to Allah whenever they slip. Repentance is not a one-time act but a lifestyle of continuous return to Allah.",
    "who are devoted to worship,": "Al-'abidun—worshippers who dedicate themselves to serving Allah through prayer, devotion, and obedience. Worship defines their identity.",
    "who praise ˹their Lord˺,": "Al-hamidun—those who praise Allah in all circumstances, grateful in ease and patient in hardship, recognizing His blessings constantly.",
    "who fast,": "Al-sa'ihun—literally 'travelers,' interpreted by most scholars as those who fast. Fasting is a journey of self-discipline, leaving bodily desires to draw closer to Allah.",
    "who bow down and prostrate themselves,": "Al-raki'un al-sajidun—those who pray, performing the physical acts of submission. Bowing and prostrating represent complete surrender to Allah.",
    "who encourage good and forbid evil,": "Al-amirun bil-ma'ruf wal-nahun 'an al-munkar—those who actively promote righteousness and prevent wrongdoing in society. Faith isn't passive; it transforms communities.",
    "and who observe the limits set by Allah.": "Al-hafizun li-hududillah—guardians of Allah's boundaries, never crossing into the forbidden, carefully staying within permissible limits. They respect divine law completely.",
    "And give good news to the believers.": "Bashshir al-mu'minin—announce glad tidings to those who embody these qualities. The characteristics listed describe the believers who made the transaction with Allah. For them: eternal good news of Paradise awaits."
  },
  113: {
    "It is not ˹proper˺ for the Prophet and the believers to seek forgiveness for the polytheists,": "A clear prohibition: the Prophet and believers cannot make istighfar (asking Allah's forgiveness) for those who died in shirk. However beloved they might have been, however close the relationship, praying for Allah to forgive their polytheism is not permitted.",
    "even if they were close relatives,": "Family bonds don't change this ruling. The Prophet's uncle Abu Talib, who protected him for decades, died without accepting Islam. The Prophet loved him dearly but couldn't pray for his forgiveness after his death in disbelief. Emotional attachment cannot override theological reality.",
    "after it has become clear to the believers that they are bound for the Hellfire.": "The condition is certainty: once it becomes clear that someone died in polytheism and is therefore destined for Hell, praying for their forgiveness becomes meaningless and improper. Forgiveness prayer implies hope for Paradise, but those who die in shirk have no such hope (as Allah has informed us). Praying for them contradicts what Allah has revealed."
  },
  114: {
    "As for Abraham's prayer for his father's forgiveness, it was only in fulfilment of a promise he had made to him.": "Someone might ask: 'But Ibrahim prayed for his polytheist father!' Allah explains: Ibrahim had promised his father to pray for him, hoping he would eventually accept faith. While his father was alive and guidance remained possible, Ibrahim kept this promise.",
    "But when it became clear to Abraham that his father was an enemy of Allah, he broke ties with him.": "Once Ibrahim realized his father would die as 'an enemy of Allah'—persisting in shirk with no hope of change—he dissociated from him (tabarra'a). He could no longer pray for his forgiveness. The hope that justified the prayer had ended; continuing would be inappropriate.",
    "Abraham was truly tender-hearted, forbearing.": "Ibrahim is described as 'awwah' (deeply emotional, tenderhearted, one who sighs and moans in devotion) and 'halim' (forbearing, patient, gentle). His dissociation from his father wasn't from coldness but from obedience to Allah despite his soft heart. This made his sacrifice even greater—he acted on principle against his natural inclination."
  },
  115: {
    "Allah would never consider a people deviant after He has guided them, until He makes clear to them what they must avoid.": "Some companions had prayed for deceased polytheist relatives before this prohibition was revealed. This verse reassures them: Allah doesn't hold people accountable for things they didn't know were forbidden. They weren't sinning before the ruling came—how could they be? Allah always clarifies what's prohibited before holding anyone responsible.",
    "Surely Allah has ˹full˺ knowledge of everything.": "Allah knows who acted in ignorance and who acts knowingly. His perfect knowledge ensures perfect justice. No one is punished for what they couldn't have known was wrong."
  },
  116: {
    "Indeed, to Allah ˹alone˺ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth.": "All sovereignty belongs exclusively to Allah. The heavens with their vastness, the earth with its complexity—all are His domain. He rules absolutely with no partner or challenger.",
    "He gives life and causes death.": "The fundamental powers of creating and ending life belong to Him alone. Every birth and every death occur by His command. This reminds believers that sacrifice for His cause is giving Him what He already controls.",
    "And besides Allah you have no guardian or helper.": "Without Allah, believers have no wali (protecting guardian) or nasir (helper in adversity). All other sources of support are illusory or temporary. This truth motivates complete reliance on Him."
  },
  117: {
    "Allah has certainly turned in mercy to the Prophet as well as the Emigrants and the Helpers": "Allah accepted the repentance and showed special favor to the Prophet (peace be upon him) and his community—both Emigrants and Helpers. 'Taba' here indicates Allah turning toward them with mercy and acceptance.",
    "who stood by him in the time of hardship,": "'Sa'at al-'usrah' (the hour of hardship) refers to the Tabuk expedition—extreme heat, scarce resources, long distance, powerful enemy. The expedition was called 'Jaysh al-'Usrah' (the Army of Hardship). Those who participated despite these difficulties earned special divine favor.",
    "after the hearts of a group of them had almost faltered.": "Even some sincere believers nearly wavered ('yakad yazighu qulub')—the hardship was so severe that their resolve almost cracked. They didn't abandon the expedition, but they came close to hesitating. This honest acknowledgment shows that faith struggles are normal; what matters is perseverance.",
    "He then accepted their repentance.": "Despite their moment of near-wavering, Allah forgave them. Their completion of the duty, despite inner struggle, earned His mercy. The struggle itself, overcome through faith, became meritorious.",
    "Surely He is Ever Gracious and Most Merciful to them.": "Allah is Ra'uf (gentle, compassionate, gracious) and Rahim (merciful) toward these believers. His kindness encompassed their weakness; His mercy covered their moments of difficulty."
  },
  118: {
    "And ˹Allah has also turned in mercy to˺ the three who had remained behind,": "These are Ka'b ibn Malik, Murarah ibn al-Rabi', and Hilal ibn Umayyah (may Allah be pleased with them)—the sincere believers who stayed behind without excuse and truthfully confessed. They were 'khullifu' (left behind in decision) for fifty days while their fate was determined.",
    "˹whose guilt distressed them˺ until the earth, despite its vastness, seemed to close in on them,": "Ka'b described this period vividly: the wide earth felt suffocating. Everyone avoided them; even their families were distanced. The vast world became a narrow prison of isolation and anxiety.",
    "and their souls were torn in anguish.": "Their own selves—their inner beings—constricted with grief. They couldn't find peace within or without. External isolation combined with internal anguish created unbearable distress.",
    "They knew there was no refuge from Allah except in Him.": "This realization was their salvation. They understood that fleeing from Allah was impossible; the only escape from Allah's displeasure was toward Allah's mercy. They had nowhere to turn except to Him, and that turning became their rescue.",
    "Then He turned to them in mercy so that they might repent.": "After fifty days, Quranic revelation announced their forgiveness. Allah's turning (tawbah) toward them enabled their turning (tawbah) toward Him. Divine mercy preceded and enabled human repentance.",
    "Surely Allah ˹alone˺ is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful.": "Al-Tawwab al-Rahim—these divine names conclude the story. Allah constantly accepts repentance; His mercy is ever-ready. Ka'b later said this was the happiest moment of his life—the day his repentance was accepted and announced from the heavens."
  },
  119: {
    "O believers! Be mindful of Allah": "A general call to all believers: maintain taqwa—consciousness of Allah that protects from sin. This awareness should govern all decisions and actions.",
    "and be with the truthful.": "'Kunu ma'a al-sadiqeen'—accompany, align with, be counted among the truthful. The three forgiven companions were saved by their truthfulness—they refused to lie despite the temptation. Truthfulness in speech and in life is the believer's character. Choose truthful companions; be truthful yourself. This quality, demonstrated powerfully by Ka'b and his companions, is what believers should emulate."
  },
  120: {
    "It was not ˹proper˺ for the people of Medina and the nomadic Arabs around them to avoid marching with the Messenger of Allah": "This establishes the obligation: Medina's residents and surrounding Bedouins should not have stayed behind when the Prophet called for the Tabuk expedition. Avoiding his call was improper, especially given their proximity and ability.",
    "or to prefer their own lives above his.": "They shouldn't value their comfort and safety more than the Prophet's. If he endured heat, hunger, and danger, how could they justify staying comfortable at home? Their lives were not more precious than his; their convenience shouldn't override his call.",
    "That is because whenever they suffer from thirst,": "Every hardship counts. Thirst (zama') in the desert march—written as a good deed.",
    "fatigue,": "Nasab—exhaustion, tiredness from the journey—written as reward.",
    "or hunger in the cause of Allah;": "Makhmasah—hunger, empty stomachs—when endured for Allah's cause, recorded as righteous action.",
    "or tread on a territory, unnerving the disbelievers;": "Every step into enemy territory that strikes fear into disbelievers' hearts—documented as good deed.",
    "or inflict any loss on an enemy—": "Any damage to the enemy—whether through battle, strategic advantage, or resource denial—earns reward.",
    "it is written to their credit as a good deed.": "Nothing is lost. Every moment of hardship, every step forward, every discomfort endured for Allah's cause is meticulously recorded and rewarded. The angels write it all.",
    "Surely Allah never discounts the reward of the good-doers.": "Allah doesn't waste the efforts of muhsineen (those who do good). Not a single moment of sacrifice goes unrewarded. This should motivate maximum effort—everything counts, nothing is forgotten."
  },
  121: {
    "And whenever they make a donation, small or large,": "Whether the contribution is tiny or substantial—a few dates or a mountain of gold—it's recorded. The poor man's small offering counts just as the rich man's large donation counts. Quality of intention matters more than quantity of gift.",
    "or cross a valley ˹in Allah's cause˺—": "Every valley crossed—a geographical marker of distance traveled—is noted. The journey itself, each segment of it, earns reward. Not just arrival at the destination but every step of the journey is accounted for.",
    "it is written to their credit,": "All of it—donations and distances—recorded in their books of deeds. The recording ensures nothing is lost or forgotten.",
    "so that Allah may grant them the best reward for what they used to do.": "Allah will reward them 'ahsan ma kanu ya'malun'—the best of what they did. Some scholars say Allah rewards them according to their best deeds; others say He gives them better than what they deserve. Either way, divine generosity ensures they receive more than they could imagine. Every sacrifice, every hardship, every small deed becomes a building block of eternal reward."
  },
  122: {
    "˹However,˺ it is not necessary for the believers to march forth all at once.": "After emphasizing the importance of jihad, this verse provides crucial balance. Not every believer must participate in every military expedition. Total mobilization isn't always required or even beneficial. The Muslim community has diverse needs, and not everyone abandoning other duties serves Islam well. This prevents extreme interpretations that demand universal military participation regardless of circumstances.",
    "Only a party from each group should march forth,": "From each tribe, region, or community, a sufficient group should go for military duty. This ensures defense while maintaining other essential functions of society. Some go to fight; others stay for equally important purposes.",
    "leaving the rest to gain religious knowledge": "Those who remain should dedicate themselves to 'yatafaqqahu fi al-deen'—deep understanding of religion. 'Tafaqquh' means comprehensive study, not superficial learning. This establishes that seeking religious knowledge is a communal obligation parallel to military defense. The Muslim community needs scholars as much as it needs soldiers. Ignorant communities cannot sustain themselves spiritually.",
    "then enlighten their people when they return to them,": "The knowledge gained must be shared. When the fighters return, those who stayed and studied should teach them. Knowledge isn't for hoarding but for spreading. Every community needs educators who can explain Islamic teachings to others. This creates a sustainable system of religious education.",
    "so that they ˹too˺ may beware ˹of evil˺.": "'La'allahum yahzarun'—so they may be cautious, guard against error, avoid sins. The purpose of knowledge is practical: helping people avoid what displeases Allah. True Islamic education produces God-consciousness and righteous action, not mere intellectual exercise. This verse beautifully balances military jihad with educational jihad—both are essential for the community's survival and prosperity."
  },
  123: {
    "O believers! Fight the disbelievers around you": "This command addresses practical military strategy. 'Alladhina yalunakum' (those nearest to you) indicates dealing with threats in order of proximity. Secure your immediate surroundings before addressing distant enemies. This was the early Muslim strategy: first the Arabian Peninsula, then expanding outward. It's logical—you cannot project power far away while threats exist nearby. This doesn't mean only fighting neighbors forever but prioritizing based on strategic reality.",
    "and let them find firmness in you.": "'Ghilzah' means toughness, sternness, firmness—not cruelty or injustice, but strength that commands respect. Enemies should not find Muslims to be weak, easily intimidated, or quick to surrender. This firmness is a deterrent; enemies who know Muslims will fight firmly are less likely to attack. It's the opposite of the soft, apologetic stance that invites aggression. However, this firmness is balanced elsewhere with commands for justice, mercy, and proportionality.",
    "And know that Allah is with those mindful ˹of Him˺.": "Divine support comes with taqwa (God-consciousness). Firmness without righteousness is mere brutality; firmness with taqwa is blessed strength. Allah's companionship ('ma'iyyah') means His help, guidance, and support. Believers who maintain their consciousness of Allah while defending their community have the ultimate ally. This conditions the command to fight: be firm, but remain righteous; be strong, but stay mindful of Allah's limits."
  },
  124: {
    "Whenever a sûrah is revealed, some of them ask ˹mockingly˺, \"Which of you has this increased in faith?\"": "Hypocrites responded to new revelations with sarcasm and mockery. When a new surah came—fresh divine guidance—they would sneer: 'So, has anyone's faith actually increased from this?' Their question drips with contempt. They couldn't understand how words could strengthen faith because they had no faith to strengthen. Their mockery revealed their inner emptiness.",
    "As for the believers, it has increased them in faith": "The same revelation that hypocrites mocked genuinely increased believers' iman. This confirms that faith is not static—it grows with knowledge, obedience, and exposure to Allah's words. Each verse, each command, each story in the Quran can elevate a believer's faith when received with an open heart. The Quran is spiritual nourishment; believers who consume it grow stronger.",
    "and they rejoice.": "'Yastabshirun'—they receive glad tidings, they rejoice, they are happy. New revelation was cause for celebration among true believers. More guidance! More wisdom! More connection to Allah! While hypocrites sneered, believers beamed with joy. The same rain that grows flowers in a garden rots dead wood—the difference is in the recipient, not the rain."
  },
  125: {
    "But as for those with sickness in their hearts,": "'Marad' (disease, sickness) in the heart refers to hypocrisy, doubt, and spiritual corruption. Their hearts were not healthy vessels ready to receive truth but infected organs that rejected nourishment. This 'disease' terminology appears throughout the Quran for hypocrisy—it's a spiritual illness that distorts perception and response.",
    "it has increased them only in wickedness upon their wickedness,": "The same revelation that increased believers' faith increased hypocrites' 'rijs' (filth, wickedness, abomination). How? Because they rejected it, mocked it, and hardened their hearts against it. Each rejection added to their sin. Each mockery deepened their corruption. They accumulated wickedness layer upon layer. The Quran, which should have been their cure, became evidence against them because of how they received it.",
    "and they die as disbelievers.": "The tragic conclusion: they die in kufr. Their disease was never treated; it only worsened until death finalized their state. They had access to the ultimate medicine—divine revelation—but refused to take it. They died spiritually diseased, and their death certificate reads 'kafirun' (disbelievers). Nothing could be worse."
  },
  126: {
    "Do they not see that they are tried once or twice every year?": "Allah tests the hypocrites repeatedly—'fitnah' (trial, test) comes to them regularly, once or twice annually. These tests include military expeditions they must join or excuse themselves from, revelations that expose their attitudes, events that reveal their true loyalties. Each test is an opportunity for reflection and repentance. The frequency shows Allah's mercy—multiple chances to wake up.",
    "Yet they neither repent": "Despite repeated testing and exposure, they don't turn back to Allah in tawbah. Each test should prompt self-reflection: 'Am I failing these tests? Am I on the wrong path?' But they remain stubborn, refusing to change course despite clear signs that something is wrong.",
    "nor do they learn a lesson.": "'Yaddakkarun'—they don't remember, reflect, or take heed. The purpose of trials is to teach, to remind, to correct. But these people learn nothing. They experience the same patterns repeatedly without ever adjusting. It's like failing a test over and over while refusing to study. Their inability to learn from experience demonstrates the depth of their spiritual death."
  },
  127: {
    "Whenever a sûrah is revealed, they look at one another,": "The hypocrites' behavior during revelation is captured vividly. When new verses came—especially ones exposing hypocrisy—they would exchange knowing glances. Their eyes would meet, silently communicating: 'This is about us. We need to be careful.' These furtive looks showed their guilty awareness.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"Is anyone watching you?\"": "They would check if believers were observing them. 'Can we slip away without being noticed?' Their concern wasn't with the content of revelation but with escaping scrutiny. They wanted to leave before their reactions betrayed them or before they had to respond to challenging verses.",
    "Then they slip away.": "'Insarafu'—they turn away, sneak off, disappear. Rather than staying to absorb Allah's words, they remove themselves. Their physical departure mirrors their spiritual departure. They can't bear to stay in the presence of truth that condemns them.",
    "˹It is˺ Allah ˹Who˺ has turned their hearts away": "'Sarafa Allahu qulubahum'—Allah turned their hearts as they turned their bodies. When they physically departed from guidance, Allah spiritually sealed their hearts from it. This is divine justice: they chose to turn away, so Allah confirmed their turning. Their outer action reflected inner reality, and Allah made the inner reality permanent.",
    "because they are a people who do not comprehend.": "The reason for their sealed hearts: they lack understanding ('la yafqahun'). Not that they couldn't understand intellectually, but they refused to understand with their hearts. True comprehension requires openness; they closed themselves. Their lack of fiqh (deep understanding) led to their rejection, which led to Allah sealing their hearts—a downward spiral of their own making."
  },
  128: {
    "There certainly has come to you a messenger from among yourselves.": "Allah highlights the Prophet's (peace be upon him) origin: 'min anfusikum'—from your own selves. He's not a stranger, not an angel, not from a distant land. He's Arab like them, human like them, from their own community. This makes him accessible, relatable, and his example followable. They know his lineage, his character, his history. No one can claim he's foreign or doesn't understand them.",
    "He is concerned by your suffering,": "'Azizun 'alayhi ma 'anittum'—he finds your hardship difficult to bear. 'Anitum' refers to suffering, hardship, distress. The Prophet genuinely grieves when his ummah suffers. Your pain pains him. He's not indifferent to human struggle; he carries the weight of his community's difficulties in his heart. This isn't political concern but authentic emotional investment.",
    "anxious for your well-being,": "'Harisun 'alaykum'—intensely eager, deeply concerned for your guidance and welfare. He desperately wants good for you. His preaching wasn't professional obligation but passionate desire for people's salvation. He stayed awake at night worrying about his ummah. He wept for those who rejected guidance because he knew what awaited them.",
    "and gracious and merciful to the believers.": "'Ra'uf'—tender, gentle, compassionate. 'Rahim'—merciful. These are two of Allah's own names applied to the Prophet regarding believers. With those who believed, he was extraordinarily kind and gentle. He forgave their mistakes, overlooked their faults, supported them through difficulties, and treated them with parental affection. This verse presents the complete portrait of prophetic character: human origin, empathic heart, eager concern, and gentle mercy."
  },
  129: {
    "But if they turn away,": "If people reject this compassionate messenger, if they turn their backs on this mercy sent to them, if despite all his concern they refuse guidance—then the Prophet is given what to say. Their rejection doesn't destroy him or his mission.",
    "then say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Allah is sufficient for me.": "'Hasbiya Allah'—Allah is enough for me. This declaration of sufficiency (hasbala) is one of the most powerful statements of faith. It means: I need nothing else, I fear no one else, I rely on no one else. If all humanity rejects me, Allah is enough. This was Ibrahim's statement when thrown into fire (3:173). It's the ultimate expression of tawakkul (trust in Allah).",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him.": "The foundational statement of tawhid—Allah's absolute oneness. This reaffirmation at the surah's end brings everything back to basics. All discussions of hypocrites, battles, treaties, and struggles ultimately center on this truth: there is only one God deserving worship, and He is Allah.",
    "In Him I put my trust.": "'Alayhi tawakkaltu'—upon Him alone I rely. Trust is placed specifically and exclusively in Allah. Not in numbers, wealth, allies, or abilities—only in Allah. This trust doesn't mean inaction but means that while taking necessary steps, the heart depends on Allah for outcomes.",
    "And He is the Lord of the Mighty Throne.\"": "'Rabb al-'arsh al-'azim'—Lord of the Magnificent Throne. The Throne ('Arsh) represents Allah's dominion over all creation. It's the greatest created thing, encompassing the heavens and earth. By mentioning this, the Prophet declares trust in the One whose authority is absolute and universal. If the Lord of the Magnificent Throne is with you, what can any enemy do? This powerful conclusion to Surah At-Tawbah leaves believers with ultimate confidence: despite all the challenges discussed—hypocrites, warfare, treachery—Allah's servants have the Lord of the Throne as their protector. Nothing else matters."
  }
};